{"title_page": "Reservoir, Victoria", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = suburb\n| name     = Reservoir\n| city     = Melbourne\n| state    = vic\n| image    =\n| caption  =\n| lga      = City of Darebin\n| alternative_location_map = Australia Victoria metropolitan Melbourne\n| coordinates = {{coord|37.713|S|145.012|E|display=inline,title}}\n| postcode = 3073\n| pop      = 50,474\n| pop_year = 2016\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=ABS2016>{{Census 2016 AUS | id = SSC22149 | name = Reservoir (State Suburb) | accessdate = 2017-07-03 | quick = on}}</ref>\n| area     = 19.1\n| established =\n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Preston|Preston]]\n| stategov2 = [[Electoral district of Thomastown|Thomastown]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Cooper|Cooper]]\n| dist1    = 12\n| location1= [[Melbourne city centre|Melbourne]]\n| dist2    =\n| location2=\n| near-nw  = [[Campbellfield, Victoria|Campbellfield]], [[Thomastown, Victoria|Thomastown]]\n| near-n   = [[Thomastown, Victoria|Thomastown]]\n| near-ne  = [[Bundoora, Victoria|Bundoora]]\n| near-w   = [[Fawkner, Victoria|Fawkner]]\n| near-e   = [[Kingsbury, Victoria|Kingsbury]]\n| near-sw  = [[Coburg North, Victoria|Coburg North]]\n| near-s   = [[Preston, Victoria|Preston]]\n| near-se  = [[Heidelberg West, Victoria|Heidelberg West]]\n}}\n\n'''Reservoir''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|\u025b|z|\u0259|v|\u0254\u02d0}}) is a suburb of [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]], 12&nbsp;km north of Melbourne's [[Melbourne City Centre|Central Business District]]. Its [[Local government areas of Victoria|local government area]] is the [[City of Darebin]]. At the [[Census in Australia#2016|2016 Census]], Reservoir had a population of 50,474.<ref name=ABS2016/> \n\nReservoir is an established suburb with standard brick homes, weatherboard homes, and an increasing number of new developments. The region contains popular recreation areas and facilities, including [[Edwardes Lake]] and the Reservoir Leisure Centre, and is home to the Edwardes Street and Broadway shopping strips.\n\n==History==\nThe land which became the suburb of Reservoir was first surveyed by [[Robert Hoddle]] in 1837 and was formed from parts of both the Jika Jika Parish and Keelbundoora Parish.<ref name = \"DarebinLibraries\">{{Citation\n  | last = Darebin Heritage - Reservoir  | title = Darebin Libraries | url = http://heritage.darebinlibraries.vic.gov.au/article/422 | accessdate = 7 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Rose Shamrock Hotel opened on Plenty Road in 1854.<ref name = \"RoseShamrock\">{{Citation | last = Darebin Heritage - Preston  | title = Darebin Heritage | url = http://heritage.darebinlibraries.vic.gov.au/article/476 | accessdate = 24 April 2014}}</ref> Reservoir Post Office opened around 1921.<ref name = \"PostOffice\">{{Citation | last = Premier Postal History  | title = Post Office List | url = https://www.premierpostal.com/cgi-bin/wsProd.sh/Viewpocdwrapper.p?SortBy=VIC&country= | accessdate = 11 April 2008}}</ref> Reservoir became a suburb at this time with the name coming from the three water reservoirs first built in 1863. \n\nThe reservoirs were collectively known as Preston Reservoir, which continue to form part of the fresh water supplied to Melbourne\u2019s inner and western suburbs.<ref name = \"PrestonReservoir\">{{Citation | last = Preston Reservoir landscape master plan  | title = Melbourne Water | url = http://melbournewater.com.au/whatwedo/projectsaroundmelbourne/Pages/Preston-Reservoir-landscape-master-plan.aspx | accessdate = 7 April 2014}}</ref> Preston Reservoir No.1, on the west of High Street, was excavated in 1863-64 and the clay was used to form the surrounding embankments, with the base and sides lined with bluestone pitchers. The reservoir commenced supplying water in 1864. The Maroondah Aqueduct was built in 1886\u20131891 to supply water to the Preston Reservoir from a diversion weir on the [[Watts River]], which was dammed in 1927 to form [[Maroondah Reservoir]]. Until 1881 Preston Reservoir was Melbourne\u2019s only service reservoir. By 1884 it was determined that Preston Reservoir needed additional water storage and an area of approximately 11ha was purchased on the east side of High Street. Reservoirs No.2 and No.3 were constructed in 1909 and 1913 respectively. Eventually reservoirs No.2 and No.3 were covered to prevent dust entering the water supply.<ref>[https://www.melbournewater.com.au/what-we-are-doing/works-and-projects-near-me/all-projects/preston-reservoir-landscape-master-plan Preston Reservoir landscape master plan]</ref>\n\nIn 1914 Thomas Dyer Edwardes donated an area of 34 acres of land to the people of the former City of Preston, which was developed into Edwardes Lake Park.<ref name = \"EdwardesLake\">{{Citation | last = Edwardes Lake Park  | title = Darebin City Council | url = http://www.darebin.vic.gov.au/Page/page.aspx?page_Id=3382 | accessdate = 24 April 2014}}</ref> Between 1919 and 1939 swimming was officially permitted with the presence of the Preston Lifesaving Club and regular demonstrations of swimming and lifesaving techniques during this time.<ref name = \"EdwardesSwimming\">{{Citation | last = Swimming at Edwardes Lake  | title = Darebin Heritage | url = http://heritage.darebinlibraries.vic.gov.au/article/429 | accessdate = 24 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nReservoir is close to the [[Northland Shopping Centre]], Preston Market, [http://www.prestoncentral.org.au/directory.html#37 High Street food quarter], [[Sydney Road, Melbourne|Sydney Road]] shops and restaurants and one of three remaining drive-in cinemas in Melbourne, the [[Village Roadshow|Village]] in [[Coburg, Victoria|Coburg]]. The area is experiencing unprecedented growth, with plenty of new developments. It is also very popular with young home-buyers looking for a 'still affordable' inner city lifestyle.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n\n==Demographics==\n\nThe most common ancestries in Reservoir were, according to the 2016 census, Italian 17.1%, Australian 14.8%, English 13.9%, Greek 6.3% and Irish 5.1%.\n55.9% of people were born in Australia. The most common countries of birth were Italy 8.2%, India 4.4%, China (excludes SARs and Taiwan) 3.2%, Greece 3.0% and Vietnam 1.8%.\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Regent Railway Station.jpg|left|thumb|[[Regent railway station]]]]\nThe area is serviced by four railway stations on the [[Mernda railway line]]: [[Reservoir railway station|Reservoir]], [[Regent railway station|Regent]], [[Keon Park railway station|Keon Park]], and [[Ruthven railway station|Ruthven]].  \n\nThe Victorian Government has announced that it will build a [[suburban rail loop]], which will include a station at Reservoir.<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-28/melbourne-suburban-train-loop-promised-by-labor/10172184</ref> \n\nReservoir station acts a bus hub for many of the Reservoir [[List of Melbourne bus routes|bus routes]].\n\nTwo tram lines service the area with the [[Melbourne tram route 11|Tram route 11: West Preston - Victoria Harbour Docklands]] terminating at the south end of Reservoir and the [[Melbourne tram route 86|Tram route 86: Bundoora RMIT - Waterfront City Docklands]] passing through Reservoir along Plenty Road.\nThe [[Merri Creek Trail]] and [[Darebin Creek Trail]] are shared-use recreational paths used by cyclists and walkers that pass through Reservoir.\n\nReservoir has easy access to the [[Western Ring Road|Northern/Western Ring Rd]], [[Hume Highway|Hume Highway/Freeway]], [[Tullamarine Freeway|Tullamarine]] & [[Calder Freeway]]s and [[Eastern Freeway, Melbourne|Eastern Freeway]].\n\n==Education==\n* [http://www.ssreservoireast.catholic.edu.au St Stephen's Parish Primary School]\n* [http://www.hnpe.catholic.edu.au Holy Name Primary School]\n* [http://www.reservoirps.vic.edu.au Reservoir Primary School]\n* [http://www.reps.vic.edu.au Reservoir East Primary School]\n* [http://www.reservoirviewsps.vic.edu.au Reservoir Views Primary School]\n* [http://www.rwps.vic.edu.au Reservoir West Primary School]\n* [http://www.sgreservoir.catholic.edu.au St Gabriel's Parish Primary School]\n* [[Reservoir High School (Victoria)|Reservoir High School]]\n* [http://www.williamruthvensc.vic.edu.au William Ruthven Secondary College]\n\n==Sport==\n\n* [[Reservoir Football Club]] and [[West Preston Football Club]] are [[Australian Rules football]] teams. Both compete in the [[Northern Football League (Australia)|Northern Football League]].<ref name = \"footy\">{{Citation  | last = Full Points Footy  | title = Northern Football League\n| url = http://www.fullpointsfooty.net/diamond_valley_football_league.htm | accessdate = 15 April 2009}}</ref>\n*\n* [http://northern.rugbynet.com.au/ Northern Rugby Union Football Club]\n* [[Preston Lions FC]] play soccer in the [[Victorian State League Division 1]] at [[B.T. Connor Reserve]]. \n* [http://www.ndadarts.org.au Northern Darts Association]\n* [http://www.northsiderollers.com Northside Roller Derby]\n\nVictorian cricketer [[Ray Harvey]] lives in Reservoir.\n\n==See also==\n* [[City of Preston (Victoria)|City of Preston]] - the former local government area of which Reservoir was a part\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{City of Darebin suburbs}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Melbourne]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = suburb\n| name     = Reservoir\n| city     = Melbourne\n| state    = vic\n| image    =\n| caption  =\n| lga      = City of Darebin\n| alternative_location_map = Australia Victoria metropolitan Melbourne\n| coordinates = {{coord|37.713|S|145.012|E|display=inline,title}}\n| postcode = 3073\n| pop      = 50,474\n| pop_year = 2016\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=ABS2016>{{Census 2016 AUS | id = SSC22149 | name = Reservoir (State Suburb) | accessdate = 2017-07-03 | quick = on}}</ref>\n| area     = 19.1\n| established =\n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Preston|Preston]]\n| stategov2 = [[Electoral district of Thomastown|Thomastown]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Cooper|Cooper]]\n| dist1    = 12\n| location1= [[Melbourne city centre|Melbourne]]\n| dist2    =\n| location2=\n| near-nw  = [[Campbellfield, Victoria|Campbellfield]], [[Thomastown, Victoria|Thomastown]]\n| near-n   = [[Thomastown, Victoria|Thomastown]]\n| near-ne  = [[Bundoora, Victoria|Bundoora]]\n| near-w   = [[Fawkner, Victoria|Fawkner]]\n| near-e   = [[Kingsbury, Victoria|Kingsbury]]\n| near-sw  = [[Coburg North, Victoria|Coburg North]]\n| near-s   = [[Preston, Victoria|Preston]]\n| near-se  = [[Heidelberg West, Victoria|Heidelberg West]]\n}}\n\n'''Reservoir''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|\u025b|z|\u0259|v|\u0254\u02d0}}) is a suburb of [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]], 12&nbsp;km north of Melbourne's [[Melbourne City Centre|Central Business District]]. Its [[Local government areas of Victoria|local government area]] is the [[City of Darebin]]. At the [[Census in Australia#2016|2016 Census]], Reservoir had a population of 50,474.<ref name=ABS2016/> \n\nReservoir is an established suburb with standard brick homes, weatherboard homes, and an increasing number of new developments. The region contains popular recreation areas and facilities, including Edwardes Lake and the Reservoir Leisure Centre, and is home to the Edwardes Street and Broadway shopping strips.\n\n==History==\nThe land which became the suburb of Reservoir was first surveyed by [[Robert Hoddle]] in 1837 and was formed from parts of both the Jika Jika Parish and Keelbundoora Parish.<ref name = \"DarebinLibraries\">{{Citation\n  | last = Darebin Heritage - Reservoir  | title = Darebin Libraries | url = http://heritage.darebinlibraries.vic.gov.au/article/422 | accessdate = 7 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Rose Shamrock Hotel opened on Plenty Road in 1854.<ref name = \"RoseShamrock\">{{Citation | last = Darebin Heritage - Preston  | title = Darebin Heritage | url = http://heritage.darebinlibraries.vic.gov.au/article/476 | accessdate = 24 April 2014}}</ref> Reservoir Post Office opened around 1921.<ref name = \"PostOffice\">{{Citation | last = Premier Postal History  | title = Post Office List | url = https://www.premierpostal.com/cgi-bin/wsProd.sh/Viewpocdwrapper.p?SortBy=VIC&country= | accessdate = 11 April 2008}}</ref> Reservoir became a suburb at this time with the name coming from the three water reservoirs first built in 1863. \n\nThe reservoirs were collectively known as Preston Reservoir, which continue to form part of the fresh water supplied to Melbourne\u2019s inner and western suburbs.<ref name = \"PrestonReservoir\">{{Citation | last = Preston Reservoir landscape master plan  | title = Melbourne Water | url = http://melbournewater.com.au/whatwedo/projectsaroundmelbourne/Pages/Preston-Reservoir-landscape-master-plan.aspx | accessdate = 7 April 2014}}</ref> Preston Reservoir No.1, on the west of High Street, was excavated in 1863-64 and the clay was used to form the surrounding embankments, with the base and sides lined with bluestone pitchers. The reservoir commenced supplying water in 1864. The Maroondah Aqueduct was built in 1886\u20131891 to supply water to the Preston Reservoir from a diversion weir on the [[Watts River]], which was dammed in 1927 to form [[Maroondah Reservoir]]. Until 1881 Preston Reservoir was Melbourne\u2019s only service reservoir. By 1884 it was determined that Preston Reservoir needed additional water storage and an area of approximately 11ha was purchased on the east side of High Street. Reservoirs No.2 and No.3 were constructed in 1909 and 1913 respectively. Eventually reservoirs No.2 and No.3 were covered to prevent dust entering the water supply.<ref>[https://www.melbournewater.com.au/what-we-are-doing/works-and-projects-near-me/all-projects/preston-reservoir-landscape-master-plan Preston Reservoir landscape master plan]</ref>\n\nIn 1914 Thomas Dyer Edwardes donated an area of 34 acres of land to the people of the former City of Preston, which was developed into Edwardes Lake Park.<ref name = \"EdwardesLake\">{{Citation | last = Edwardes Lake Park  | title = Darebin City Council | url = http://www.darebin.vic.gov.au/Page/page.aspx?page_Id=3382 | accessdate = 24 April 2014}}</ref> Between 1919 and 1939 swimming was officially permitted with the presence of the Preston Lifesaving Club and regular demonstrations of swimming and lifesaving techniques during this time.<ref name = \"EdwardesSwimming\">{{Citation | last = Swimming at Edwardes Lake  | title = Darebin Heritage | url = http://heritage.darebinlibraries.vic.gov.au/article/429 | accessdate = 24 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nReservoir is close to the [[Northland Shopping Centre]], Preston Market, [http://www.prestoncentral.org.au/directory.html#37 High Street food quarter], [[Sydney Road, Melbourne|Sydney Road]] shops and restaurants and one of three remaining drive-in cinemas in Melbourne, the [[Village Roadshow|Village]] in [[Coburg, Victoria|Coburg]]. The area is experiencing unprecedented growth, with plenty of new developments. It is also very popular with young home-buyers looking for a 'still affordable' inner city lifestyle.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n\n==Demographics==\n\nThe most common ancestries in Reservoir were, according to the 2016 census, Italian 17.1%, Australian 14.8%, English 13.9%, Greek 6.3% and Irish 5.1%.\n55.9% of people were born in Australia. The most common countries of birth were Italy 8.2%, India 4.4%, China (excludes SARs and Taiwan) 3.2%, Greece 3.0% and Vietnam 1.8%.\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Regent Railway Station.jpg|left|thumb|[[Regent railway station]]]]\nThe area is serviced by four railway stations on the [[Mernda railway line]]: [[Reservoir railway station|Reservoir]], [[Regent railway station|Regent]], [[Keon Park railway station|Keon Park]], and [[Ruthven railway station|Ruthven]].  \n\nThe Victorian Government has announced that it will build a [[suburban rail loop]], which will include a station at Reservoir.<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-28/melbourne-suburban-train-loop-promised-by-labor/10172184</ref> \n\nReservoir station acts a bus hub for many of the Reservoir [[List of Melbourne bus routes|bus routes]].\n\nTwo tram lines service the area with the [[Melbourne tram route 11|Tram route 11: West Preston - Victoria Harbour Docklands]] terminating at the south end of Reservoir and the [[Melbourne tram route 86|Tram route 86: Bundoora RMIT - Waterfront City Docklands]] passing through Reservoir along Plenty Road.\nThe [[Merri Creek Trail]] and [[Darebin Creek Trail]] are shared-use recreational paths used by cyclists and walkers that pass through Reservoir.\n\nReservoir has easy access to the [[Western Ring Road|Northern/Western Ring Rd]], [[Hume Highway|Hume Highway/Freeway]], [[Tullamarine Freeway|Tullamarine]] & [[Calder Freeway]]s and [[Eastern Freeway, Melbourne|Eastern Freeway]].\n\n==Education==\n* [http://www.ssreservoireast.catholic.edu.au St Stephen's Parish Primary School]\n* [http://www.hnpe.catholic.edu.au Holy Name Primary School]\n* [http://www.reservoirps.vic.edu.au Reservoir Primary School]\n* [http://www.reps.vic.edu.au Reservoir East Primary School]\n* [http://www.reservoirviewsps.vic.edu.au Reservoir Views Primary School]\n* [http://www.rwps.vic.edu.au Reservoir West Primary School]\n* [http://www.sgreservoir.catholic.edu.au St Gabriel's Parish Primary School]\n* [[Reservoir High School (Victoria)|Reservoir High School]]\n* [http://www.williamruthvensc.vic.edu.au William Ruthven Secondary College]\n\n==Sport==\n\n* [[Reservoir Football Club]] and [[West Preston Football Club]] are [[Australian Rules football]] teams. Both compete in the [[Northern Football League (Australia)|Northern Football League]].<ref name = \"footy\">{{Citation  | last = Full Points Footy  | title = Northern Football League\n| url = http://www.fullpointsfooty.net/diamond_valley_football_league.htm | accessdate = 15 April 2009}}</ref>\n*\n* [http://northern.rugbynet.com.au/ Northern Rugby Union Football Club]\n* [[Preston Lions FC]] play soccer in the [[Victorian State League Division 1]] at [[B.T. Connor Reserve]]. \n* [http://www.ndadarts.org.au Northern Darts Association]\n* [http://www.northsiderollers.com Northside Roller Derby]\n\nVictorian cricketer [[Ray Harvey]] lives in Reservoir.\n\n==See also==\n* [[City of Preston (Victoria)|City of Preston]] - the former local government area of which Reservoir was a part\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{City of Darebin suburbs}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Melbourne]]\n", "name_user": "Garyvines", "label": "safe", "comment": "link to Edwards lane - article to come", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reservoir,_Victoria"}
{"title_page": "Bell miner", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Bell miner\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704430/0 |title=''Manorina melanophrys'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| image = Bell Miner 1 - Nepean Weir.jpg\n| genus = Manorina\n| species = melanophrys\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1801)\n| range_map=Bell Miner Distribution From Atlas Living Australia.png\n| range_map_caption=Bell miner range<ref>{{cite web|title=Manorina (Manorina) melanophrys (Latham, 1801) Bell Miner|url=http://bie.ala.org.au/species/Manorina+%28Manorina%29+melanophrys#|website=Atlas of Living Australia|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''bell miner''' (''Manorina melanophrys''), commonly known as the '''bellbird''', is a colonial [[honeyeater]], endemic to southeastern [[Australia]].  The common name refers to their bell-like call. 'Miner' is an old alternative spelling of '[[myna]]', and is shared with other members of the genus ''[[Manorina]]''.<ref>For the derivation of 'miner' from 'myna', see comment at Common Indian Myna [http://fennerschool-associated.anu.edu.au/myna/] Retrieved 12 September 2013</ref>  The birds feed almost exclusively on the dome-like coverings, referred to as 'bell lerps', of certain [[psyllid]] bugs that feed on [[eucalyptus]] sap from the leaves. The psyllids make these bell lerps from their own honeydew secretions in order to protect themselves from predators and the environment.\n\nBell miners live in large, complex, social groups.  Within each group, there are subgroups consisting of several breeding pairs, but also including a number of birds that are not currently breeding.  The nonbreeders help in providing food for the young in all the nests within the subgroup, even though they are not necessarily closely related to them.<ref name=\"Ethology\">{{cite journal | last1 = Clarke | first1 = M. F. | year = 1989 | title = The pattern of helping in the bell miner (''Manorina melanophrys'') | doi = 10.1111/j.1439-0310.1989.tb00748.x | journal = Ethology | volume = 80 | issue = 1\u20134| pages = 292\u2013306 }}</ref>  The birds defend their colony area communally and aggressively, excluding most other [[passerine]] species.  They do this in order to protect their territory from other insect-eating birds that would eat the bell lerps on which they feed.  Whenever the local forests die back, due to increased lerp psyllid infestations, bell miners undergo a population boom.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe bell miner (''Manorina melanophrys'') belongs to the family of [[honeyeater]]s and Australian chats ([[Meliphagidae]]), which is part of the superfamily [[Meliphagoidea]] that also comprises the Australian warblers, scrubwrens, and thornbills ([[Acanthizidae]]); bristlebirds ([[Dasyornithidae]]); fairy-wrens ([[Maluridae]]); and pardalotes ([[Pardalotidae]]).<ref name=\"Phylogeny\">{{cite journal|last1=Gardner|first1=Janet L.|last2=Trueman|first2=John W.H.|last3=Ebert|first3=Daniel|last4=Joseph|first4=Leo|last5=Magrath|first5=Robert D.|title=Phylogeny and evolution of the Meliphagoidea, the largest radiation of Australasian songbirds|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|date=June 2010|volume=55|issue=3|pages=1087\u20131102|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2010.02.005|pmid=20152917}}</ref>\nBell miners share the genus ''[[Manorina]]'' with three other endemic Australian miners: the [[noisy miner]] (''M. melanocephala''), the [[yellow-throated miner]] (''M. flavigula''), and the endangered [[black-eared miner]] (''M. melanotis''). The three other miners were previously classified in the genus ''Myzantha'', which is still sometimes listed as a subgenus for those species. The closest related genus to ''[[Manorina]]'' has been genetically found to be the New Guinea and New Britain ''[[Melidectes]]'' honeyeaters. The bell miner's tinkling bell-like call was noted by early European explorers, <ref name=\"AustralianBirdNames\">{{cite book|last1=Fraser|first1=Ian|last2=Gray|first2=Jeannie|title=Australian bird names : a complete guide|date=2013|publisher=CSIRO Publishing|location=Collingwood, Vic.|isbn=9780643104693|page=204}}</ref> \nand the name bellbird was considered established 30 years later, when David Collins mentioned \"the melancholy cry of the bellbird.\"\n<ref name=\"AustralianBirdNames\" />\n<ref name=\"Collins\">{{cite book|last1=Collins|first1=David|title=An Account of the English Colony of New South Wales Volume 2|date=1802|location=London|url=http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks/e00011.html|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref>\nIn 1802, John [[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]] named the bird ''Turdus melanophrys'' meaning 'black-browed thrush'.<ref name=\"AustralianBirdNames\" /><ref name=\"Latham\">{{cite book|last1=Latham|first1=J|title=Supplementum Indicis Ornithologici sive Systematis Ornithologiae|publisher=Leigh & Sotheby|date=1848|location=London|url=http://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/en/fs1/object/display/bsb10483009_00001.html?leftTab=toc|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref> While Latham's scientific name became accepted, John Gould continued to use Australian bellbird as the name for the species in 1848.<ref name=\"AustralianBirdNames\" /><ref name=\"Gould\">{{cite book|last1=Gould|first1=John|title=The Birds of Australia Volume 1-7|date=1848|location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe common name of bellbird may lead to some confusion with the Australian inland endemic [[crested bellbird]], which is of the family [[Oreoicidae]]. The two species exhibit very different calls, behaviour, and do not overlap in range.<ref name=\"Pizzey\">{{cite book|last1=Pizzey|first1=Graham|last2=Knight|first2=Frank|title=The Field Guide to the Birds of Australia|edition=Ninth|date=2012|publisher=Harper Collins|location=Sydney|isbn=9780732299828}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nBell miners are the smallest of their genus, and differ from the other three predominantly grey miner species in having olive-green plumage, darker on the wings and yellower on the belly.<ref name=\"Officer\">{{cite book|last1=Stirling|first1=Hugh R. Officer ; ill. by Peg Maltby ; map by Alex|title=Australian honeyeaters|date=1971|publisher=Bird Observers Club|location=Melbourne|isbn=978-0-909711-03-0|page=71|edition=2dwith amendments and distribution maps.}}</ref>\nThey are a medium bodied honeyeater, slightly smaller and stockier than a [[Lewin's honeyeater]] (''Meliphaga lewinii''), weighing between 25g and 35g<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\">{{cite book|last1=Higgins|first1=P. J.|last2=Peter|first2=J. M.|last3=Steele|first3=W. K.|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand & Antarctic Birds Volume 5: Tyrant-flycatchers to ChatsTyrant flycatchers to chats|date=2001|publisher=Oxford Univ. Press|location=South Melbourne [u.a.]|isbn=978-0195532586|pages=609\u2013626}}</ref>\n(average 29g).<ref name=\"BirdInBackyards:BellMiner\">{{cite web|title=Bell Miner|url=http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/species/Manorina-melanophrys|website=Birds In Backyards|publisher=Birdlife Australia|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\nBell miners are 17.5\u201320&nbsp;cm in length (average 18.5&nbsp;cm) with a 22\u201330&nbsp;cm wingspan (average 26.5&nbsp;cm).<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\nThey have the characteristic yellow bill of the miners, which is slightly downturned. The legs are bright orange, and the bare patch behind the eye is red-orange.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\nThe crown and lores are black, while the feathers in front of the eye are yellow. A dark streak runs from the corner of the bill downward<ref name=\"Officer\" />\ngiving a slight frowning appearance. Eyes are brown and mouth is yellow.<ref name=\"BandersAid\">{{cite book|last1=Ken|first1=Rogers|last2=Rogers|first2=Annie|last3=Rogers|first3=Danny|title=Bander's aid : a guide to ageing and sexing bush birds|date=1986|publisher=A. Rogers|location=St. Andrews, Vic.|isbn=978-1862526402|pages=86\u201387|url=http://birdlife.org.au/documents/OTHPUB-Banders-Aid.pdf|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\nBoth sexes look alike, though the males tend to be slightly larger.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\nIt is possible to determine the sex of the birds by analyzing wing length, tail length, and culmen depth, or by observing calls that are unique to females, but there is no easy way to reliably determine the sex in the field without careful observation of behaviour and calls.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=MF|last2=Heathcote|first2=CF|title=Methods for Sexing and Aging the Bell Miner Manorina melanophrys|journal=Emu|date=1988|volume=88|issue=2|pages=118|doi=10.1071/MU9880118}}</ref>\nJuveniles are more brown-colored than the adults and overall less bright in color. Young birds do not have the bare skin patch behind the eye. The patch initially develops as pale grey, then transforms to pale yellow, and darkens to pale orange before taking on the adult bright red-orange color as the bird matures.<ref name=\"BandersAid\" /><ref name=\"ABSA\">{{cite book|last1=Hardy|first1=J. W.|title=Bird in the Hand|edition=2nd|url=http://www.absa.asn.au/absainc/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bell-Miner.pdf|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>\nNestlings are born naked and develop light brown down about two days post hatching.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\n\nThe birds are heard more than they are seen, as bell miners tend to forage high in the [[Canopy (biology)|canopy]], and their olive-green plumage blends into the surrounding leaves. However, they keep up their \"ping\" contact call as they forage throughout the day.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> In the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Melbourne]], bell miners come low enough to be easily seen and photographed.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nBell miners are distributed from around [[Gympie]] in [[Queensland]], south along the coastal plain and ranges, to [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], around [[Melbourne]].<ref name=\"Officer\" /><ref name=\"HoneyeaterDistribution\">{{cite journal|last1=Gannon|first1=G.R.|title=Distribution of the Australian honeyeaters.|journal=Emu|date=1962|volume=62|issue=3|pages=145\u2013166|doi=10.1071/MU962145}}</ref>\nThey prefer the margins of wet or dry [[sclerophyll]] forest and thick woodlands, often with a stream or other permanent water source nearby.<ref name=\"NestEgg\">{{cite book|last1=Beruldsen|first1=Gordon|title=Australian birds their nests and eggs|date=2003|publisher=G. Beruldsen|location=Kenmore Hills, Qld.|isbn=978-0-646-42798-0|page=313|edition=rev.}}</ref>\nThis limits their range to higher rainfall areas near the coast, often bordering, but not inside, rainforest. Compared to the closely related noisy miner,<ref name =\"Birdlife\">{{cite book|last1=Rowley|first1=Ian|title=Bird life|date=1974|publisher=Collins|location=Sydney|isbn=978-0-00-211438-7|pages=119\u2013120}}</ref>\nbell miners prefer a denser habitat with a thick [[understory]] (<5 m), but a sparse midstory (5\u201315 m) and canopy (>15m).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lambert|first1=Kathryn T. A.|last2=Kumar|first2=Lalit|last3=Reid|first3=Nick|last4=McDonald|first4=Paul G.|title=Habitat selection by a despotic passerine, the Bell Miner (): When restoring habitat through Lantana () removal is not enough|journal=Ecological Management & Restoration|date=January 2016|volume=17|issue=1|pages=81\u201384|doi=10.1111/emr.12196}}</ref>\nIn an undisturbed setting, bell miners choose habitat with an understory of shrubs, ferns, sedges, and rainforest vines.<ref name=\"Thesis\">{{cite book|last1=Hastings|first1=Tony|title=Rainforests and Bell Miner Associated Dieback in Natural Ecosystems|date=May 2012|location=Charles Sturt University|page=85|url=http://www.tonyhastings.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/reports/hastings%20BMAD%20thesis.pdf|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref>\nThey have been observed to expand their range in disturbed habitats that have a thick undergrowth of the invasive weed [[lantana]].<ref name=\"LantanaMiners\">{{cite journal|last1=Somerville|first1=Susan|last2=Somerville|first2=Wayne|last3=Coyle|first3=Rodney|title=Regenerating native forest using splatter gun techniques to remove Lantana|journal=Ecological Management & Restoration|date=December 2011|volume=12|issue=3|pages=164\u2013174|doi=10.1111/j.1442-8903.2011.00608.x}}</ref>\nBell miner population densities have been measured at 14-38 birds per hectare.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kemmerer|first1=Ernst P.|last2=Shields|first2=Jim M.|last3=Tidemann|first3=Christopher R.|title=High densities of bell miners Manorina melanophrys associated with reduced diversity of other birds in wet eucalypt forest: Potential for adaptive management|journal=Forest Ecology and Management|date=April 2008|volume=255|issue=7|pages=2094\u20132102|doi=10.1016/j.foreco.2007.12.035}}</ref>\nThey are particular about their preferred habitat and reasonably small disturbances to undergrowth, such as fire or lantana removal, can cause a colony to move to a new territory.<ref name=\"NestEgg\" />\n\n==Behaviour==\n\n===Social organization===\nThe complex social organization of bell miners was observed as early as the 1960s<ref name=\"HoneyeaterDistribution\" /> in [[New South Wales]], and has been studied by several research groups in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\nBell miners live in large colonies of 8-200+ birds,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hyem|first1=E.L|title=Notes on the Birds of \"Mernot, \" Barrington, N.S.W.|journal=Emu|date=1936|volume=36|issue=4|pages=262\u2013272|doi=10.1071/MU936262}}</ref> \nwhich consist of coteries or clans of generally related male birds and their offspring. Each coterie is made up of several monogamous breeding pairs with their nest helpers.<ref name=\"GeneticStructure\">{{cite journal|last1=Painter|first1=J. N.|last2=Crozier|first2=R. H.|last3=Poiani|first3=A.|last4=Robertson|first4=R. J.|last5=Clarke|first5=M. F.|title=Complex social organization reflects genetic structure and relatedness in the cooperatively breeding bell miner, Manorina melanophrys|journal=Molecular Ecology|date=September 2000|volume=9|issue=9|pages=1339\u20131347|doi=10.1046/j.1365-294x.2000.01012.x}}</ref>\nAs a colony, bell miners are aggressive and set up a permanent territory that they will defend together against all other honeyeaters and any other species, which they perceive are a threat to their preferred food source or themselves.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\nWithin the colonial territory, each breeding pair has its own foraging range. Helpers assist multiple breeding pairs, and move between the foraging range of several pairs. Coteries are groups that are interconnected and interact daily within the larger colony, due to a close genetic relationship.<ref name=\"KinSelection\">{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=Michael F.|title=Co-operative Breeding by the Australian Bell Miner Manorina melanophrys Latham: A Test of Kin Selection Theory|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|date=1984|volume=14|issue=2|pages=137\u2013146|jstor=4599660|doi=10.1007/bf00291904}}</ref>\n\nDue to their aggressive nature, bell miners are known for excluding other birds from their territory, and larger avian species, like kookaburras, currawongs, and crows are mobbed by up to twelve miners from different coteries within the colony. Predators are repeatedly attacked, if they settle in another part of the colony's territory. Small birds that keep to the understory, like fairy-wrens, scrubwrens and blackbirds are often not driven out,<ref name=\"SocialOrganization\">{{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=AJ|last2=Robertson|first2=BI|title=Social Organization of Bell Miners|journal=Emu|date=1978|volume=78|issue=4|pages=169|doi=10.1071/MU9780169}}</ref>\nbut small birds that typically forage in the midstory or canopy or share similar foods, like pardalotes, are not allowed access within the territory. One of the few species that can sometimes displace bell miners is the similarly aggressive noisy miner, but in general noisy miners prefer areas with little understory.<ref name=\"InterspeciesAggression\">{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=MF|title=Interspecific aggression within the Genus|journal=Emu|date=1984|volume=84|issue=2|pages=113\u2013115|doi=10.1071/MU9840113}}</ref>\nBell miners are able to suppress the numbers of competing species in territory that they hold for years.<ref name=\"AsymmetricalCompetition\">{{cite journal|last1=Poiani|first1=A.|last2=Rogers|first2=A.|last3=Rogers|first3=K.|last4=Rogers|first4=D.|title=Asymmetrical competition between the bell miner (Manorina melanophrys, Meliphagidae) and other honeyeaters: evidence from Southeastern Victoria, Australia|journal=Oecologia|date=December 1990|volume=85|issue=2|pages=250\u2013256|doi=10.1007/BF00319410|pmid=28312564}}</ref> \nHowever, bell miner colonies have clearly defined territorial boundaries, and beyond those boundaries the local bird assemblage resumes its normal diversity.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leseberg|first1=Nicholas P.|last2=Lambert|first2=Kathryn T. A.|last3=McDonald|first3=Paul G.|title=Fine-scale impacts on avian biodiversity due to a despotic species, the bell miner ()|journal=Austral Ecology|date=May 2015|volume=40|issue=3|pages=245\u2013254|doi=10.1111/aec.12206}}</ref>\n\n===Feeding===\nBell miners specialize in consuming insects known as [[Jumping plant louse|psyllid]]s and their associated young nymphs, sweet [[lerp (biology)|lerps]], and other psyllid secretions. Psyllid products may consist of up to 90% of the bell miner's diet.<ref name=\"LoynScience\">{{cite journal|last1=Loyn|first1=Richard H.|title=Territorial Bell Miners and Other Birds Affecting Populations of Insect Prey|journal=Science|date=September 30, 1983|volume=221|issue=4618|pages=1411\u20133|doi=10.1126/science.221.4618.1411|pmid=17759017}}</ref> Bell miners forage primarily among leaves, branches, and loose bark in the canopy, generally at least 8 m in height, but they do descend to the dense understory.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> There is a theory that bell miners 'farm' psyllids by excluding other psyllid-eating bird species from a large enough territory that the miners themselves do not require all the psyllids to sustain the colony.<ref name=\"FarmsDell\">{{cite journal|last1=Loyn|first1=Richard H.|title=The Bird that Farms the Dell|journal=Natural History (Pre-1988)|date=June 1987|volume=96|issue=6}}</ref> One hypothesis under the farming theory is that the bell miners may selectively eat only older nymphs or may often eat the lerps and leave the nymph unharmed.<ref name=\"FarmsDell\" /> Evidence for this theory has been mixed. An early study of stomach contents did not find supporting evidence for this theory, as miner stomachs did not contain the higher lerp/nymph ratio that would have been expected.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Poiani|first1=A|title=Bell Miners: What Kind of Farmers Are They?|journal=Emu|date=1993|volume=93|issue=3|pages=188\u2013194|doi=10.1071/MU9930188}}</ref> However, a later behavioral comparison between bell miners and noisy miners did observe that bell miners carefully used their tongue to remove lerps, which left the nymph intact. In contrast, noisy miners pried the lerp and nymph off with their beak and consumed both.<ref name=\"NonLethalForage\">{{cite journal|last1=HAYTHORPE|first1=KATHRYN M.|last2=McDONALD|first2=PAUL G.|title=Non-lethal foraging by bell miners on a herbivorous insect: Potential implications for forest health|journal=Austral Ecology|date=25 February 2010|volume=35|issue=4|pages=444\u2013450|doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.2009.02099.x}}</ref> When bell miners are removed, psyllid colonies are generally quickly decimated by the other forest bird species that move into the miners' former territory.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /><ref name=\"LoynScience\" />\n\nAlthough psyllids are the primary food source, like most honeyeaters bell miners have also been recorded drinking nectar from eucalyptus, banksia, and mistletoe flowers, as well as eating various other insects including spiders, beetles, weevils, moths and wasps.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /><ref name=\"Food\">{{cite book|last1=Barker|first1=R.D.|last2=Vestjens|first2=W.J.M.|title=The food of Australian birds|date=1989|publisher=CSIRO Division of Wildlife and Ecology|location=Lyneham, A.C.T.|isbn=978-0643051157|pages=196\u2013197}}</ref>\n\n====Bell Miner Associated Dieback====\nBell miners are so closely associated with eucalyptus dieback that the phenomenon has been named Bell Miner Associated Dieback (BMAD). Concern about BMAD has led to the formation of the BMAD Working Group,<ref name=\"WorkingGroup\">{{cite web|title=Bell Miner Associated Dieback Working Group|url=http://www.bmad.com.au/workinggroup.php|website=Bell Miner Associated Dieback|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> the 2004 BMAD Strategy,<ref name=\"Strategy\">{{cite book|title=Bell Miner Associated Dieback Strategy 2004|date=2004|publisher=Bell Miner Associated Dieback Working Group|pages=1\u201319|url=http://www.bmad.com.au/publications/BMAD_Strategy_2004.pdf|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> the 2005 BMAD National Forum,<ref name=\"NationalForum\">{{cite book|title=Proceedings of the Bell Miner Associated Dieback National Forum|date=March 30, 2005|location=Southern Cross University, Lismore, Australia|url=http://www.bmad.com.au/publications/BMAD_Proceedings.pdf|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> the 2006 BMAD Literature Review,<ref name=\"LitReview\">{{cite book|last1=Wardell-Johnson|first1=Grant|last2=Stone|first2=Christine|last3=Recher|first3=Harry|last4=Lynch|first4=A. Jasmyn J.|title=Bell miner associated dieback (BMAD) independent scientific literature review : a review of eucalypt dieback associated with Bell miner habitat in north-eastern New South Wales, Australia|date=2006|publisher=Dept. of Environment and Conservation (NSW)|location=[Coffs Harbour, N.S.W.]|isbn=978-1741378566|url=http://www.bmad.com.au/publications/LiteratureReview.pdf|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> and continues to be an area of active research. Eucalyptus dieback involved complicated ecosystems with numerous variables and occurs in some habitats without the presence of bell miners,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Jurskis|first1=Vic|title=Eucalypt decline in Australia, and a general concept of tree decline and dieback|journal=Forest Ecology and Management|date=August 2005|volume=215|issue=1\u20133|pages=1\u201320|doi=10.1016/j.foreco.2005.04.026}}</ref> but there is a high correlation with bell miner presence and eucalyptus dieback that was noted as early as 1982. One theory is that the monopolising and/or farming of psyllids by bell miners allows psyllid numbers to build up, eventually leading to tree sickness and possibly death.<ref name=\"SurveyCrownDieback\">{{cite book|last1=Stone|first1=C.|last2=Spolc|first2=D.|last3=Urquhart|first3=C.A.|title=Survey of crown dieback in moist hardwood forests in the central and northern regions of New South Wales state forests (psyllid/bell miner research programme)|date=1995|publisher=Research Division, State Forests of New South Wales|location=Sydney|isbn=978-0731022168}}</ref> In some cases where bell miners have been removed the avian diversity has been restored and the psyllid infestation reduced to the point of trees returning to health.<ref name=\"LoynScience\" /> However, in other studies the trees did not recover even after bell miner removal, so more research is needed to better understand the relationship between bell miners and eucalyptus dieback.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=Michael F|last2=Schedvin|first2=Natasha|title=Removal of bell miners Manorina melanophrys from Eucalyptus radiata forest and its effect on avian diversity, psyllids and tree health|journal=Biological Conservation|date=April 1999|volume=88|issue=1|pages=111\u2013120|doi=10.1016/S0006-3207(98)00083-4}}</ref>\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:BabyBellMiner1.jpg|thumb|right|immature birds]]\nBell miners are generally sedentary and thus have a permanent all-purpose territory which includes breeding. The primary breeding season is April/May to August/September in the northern part of their range and June/July to November/December in the southern range,<ref name=\"NestEgg\" /> but breeding has been observed in all months of the year<ref name=\"SocialOrganization\" /><ref name=\"ReproductiveBehavior\">{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=MF|title=The Reproductive Behavior of the Bell Miner|journal=Emu|date=1988|volume=88|issue=2|pages=88\u2013100|doi=10.1071/MU9880088}}</ref> as females will often nest again after a failed nest or once the young have fledged. One female was recorded nesting five times in one season, though that many nest attempts is unusual.<ref name=\"SocialOrganization\" /> Bell miner pairs are monogamous, but the breeding tasks are divided between the sexes. Female bell miners build the nest over 8 days, incubate the 1-3 (but typically 2) eggs for 14.5 days, and brood the young for up to 12 days depending on the weather.<ref name=\"ReproductiveBehavior\" /> The nests are small, cup-shaped and built with dry twigs, grasses, and bark woven together with spider web.<ref name=\"NestEgg\" /> Nests are generally hidden in the foliage of dense understory plants, 3-5m above the ground.<ref name=\"NestEgg\" /> The eggs are typically 24mm x 16mm, oval shaped, and pink in color. They have darker reddish brown spots and blotches primarily over the larger end.<ref name=\"NestEgg\" /> Pallid cuckoos have been recorded as nest parasites for bell miners.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Swainson|first1=G.W.|title=Co-operative rearing in the Bell Miner|journal=Emu|date=1970|volume=70|issue=4|pages=183\u2013188|doi=10.1071/MU970183}}</ref>\n\nWhile nests are all within the territory of the colony, they are not tightly packed as traditional colony breeders. Instead nests are located within the breeding pairs' normal foraging range. They are generally within calling range of neighbour nests, but not too close.<ref name=\"SpacialOrg\">{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=MF|last2=Fitzgerald|first2=GF|title=Spatial-Organization of the Cooperatively Breeding Bell Miner|journal=Emu|date=1994|volume=94|issue=2|pages=96|doi=10.1071/MU9940096}}</ref> Female bell miners move nest locations after a nest failure and were observed to move nests lower into the thick understory, likely reducing the risk of avian predators. However, they did not move nests far from the original location horizontally, possibly to stay within their home foraging range and to retain their established set of helpers.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Beckmann|first1=Christa|last2=McDonald|first2=Paul G.|title=Placement of Re-nests Following Predation: Are Birds Managing Risk?|journal=Emu|date=2016|volume=116|pages=9\u201313|doi=10.1071/mu15064}}</ref> Females will also alter brood sex ratios to meet conditions. When a colony is in a new location with an inferior food source the ratio will be biased towards more females which will disperse from the colony at sexual maturity. Once the food supply has been increased, the brood sex ratio is shifted towards future helping males.<ref name=\"BroodSexRatio\">{{cite journal|last1=Ewen|first1=J. G.|title=Facultative control of offspring sex in the cooperatively breeding bell miner, Manorina melanophrys|journal=Behavioral Ecology|date=1 March 2003|volume=14|issue=2|pages=157\u2013164|doi=10.1093/beheco/14.2.157}}</ref>\n\n====Nest helpers====\nBoth parents and helpers provision and care for the nestlings. Nests may be attended by up to 20 helpers,<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> and nest success has been observed to be higher when there are at least 6 additional helpers attending the nest in addition to the breeding pair.<ref name=\"Ethology\" /> Helpers feed the young, defend the nest against predators, remove droppings, and remove parasites.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> Nest helpers include both sexes, but are predominately young and breeding age males. Juvenile birds start helping as early as 1.3 months old.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> Older non-breeding males contribute the most food to nestlings and assist with multiple nests.<ref name=\"Ethology\" /> The amount of help offered by a nest helper is correlated with its genetic relationship with the nestlings it is feeding.<ref name=\"KinSelection\" /> Bell miners use a provisioning call when they arrive at the nest to stimulate the young to beg. Provisioning calls are similar among closely related miners, so helpers preferentially help young with fathers which have provisioning calls similar to their own.\n<ref name=\"BeggingCalls\">{{cite journal|last1=McDonald|first1=P. G.|last2=Wright|first2=J.|title=Bell miner provisioning calls are more similar among relatives and are used by helpers at the nest to bias their effort towards kin|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences|date=30 March 2011|volume=278|issue=1723|pages=3403\u20133411|doi=10.1098/rspb.2011.0307|pmid=21450738|pmc=3177633}}</ref>\nHowever, it is important to note that even non-related helpers have been shown to contribute a significant amount to raising young,\n<ref name=\"NonRelatedHelpers\">{{cite journal|last1=Wright|first1=J.|last2=McDonald|first2=P. G.|last3=te Marvelde|first3=L.|last4=Kazem|first4=A. J. N.|last5=Bishop|first5=C. M.|title=Helping effort increases with relatedness in bell miners, but 'unrelated' helpers of both sexes still provide substantial care|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences|date=21 October 2009|volume=277|issue=1680|pages=437\u2013445|doi=10.1098/rspb.2009.1360|pmid=19846458|pmc=2842640}}</ref>\nand no difference was seen in the amount of help offered by helpers depending on the brood sex even though male chicks tend to stay with the colony and become helpers while females disperse.\n<ref>{{cite journal|last1=McDonald|first1=Paul G.|last2=Ewen|first2=John G.|last3=Wright|first3=Jonathan|title=Brood sex ratio does not affect helper effort in a cooperative bird, despite extreme sex-biased dispersal|journal=Animal Behaviour|date=January 2010|volume=79|issue=1|pages=243\u2013250|doi=10.1016/j.anbehav.2009.11.007}}</ref> \nHelpers will delay bringing food to the nestlings when the female is brooding them, but will eventually bring food even if the female continues to brood. The brooding female is more likely to allow the young to be fed if the attendant is her mate.<ref name=\"BroodingBehavior\">{{cite journal|last1=Archard|first1=G.A.|last2=Robertson|first2=R.J.|last3=Jones|first3=D.|last4=Painter|first4=J.|last5=Crozier|first5=R.|last6=Clarke|first6=M.F.|title=Brooding behaviour in the cooperatively breeding Bell Miner (Manorina melanophrys)|journal=Emu|date=1 January 2006|volume=106|issue=2|pages=105\u2013112|doi=10.1071/mu05032}}</ref>\n\n====Fledgling to adulthood====\nYoung bell miners leave the nest about 12 days post hatching, but continue to be fed by parents and helpers for a further 10 weeks.<ref name=\"ReproductiveBehavior\" /> Bell miners will start helping at nests when less than 2 months old, but the transition is gradual such that recently fledged birds will continue to beg from other helpers, and then either consume the offered food or give it to younger birds.<ref name=\"KinSelection\" /> Females tend to disperse from the colony at 8 months and they reach breeding age at 8.3 months. It is likely that as they reach maturity the mothers become intolerant of their mature daughters prompting their dispersal. The mortality of bell miners prior to breeding age is very high at 93%.<ref name=\"Dispersal\">{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=MF|last2=Heathcote|first2=CF|title=Dispersal, Survivorship and Demography in the Co-Operatively-Breeding Bell Miner|journal=Emu|date=1990|volume=90|issue=1|pages=15|doi=10.1071/MU9900015}}</ref> The greatest risk is soon after young bell miners leave the nest when many are preyed upon.<ref name=\"SocialOrganization\" /> Known predators include grey currawong, Australian raven, laughing kookaburra, brown goshawk, copperhead snake, and eastern brown snake.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> By the time they reach breeding age the sex ratio is skewed with more surviving males, probably due to higher mortality of the dispersing females.<ref name=\"Dispersal\" />\n\n[[Image:Bell Miner boulumba1.ogg|thumb|300px|left|Bouloumba Creek, SE Queensland, Australia]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Manorina melanophrys}}\n{{Wikispecies|Manorina melanophrys}}\n* Bell Miner Associated Dieback [http://www.bmad.com.au/publications.html]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3179448}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:miner, bell}}\n[[Category:Manorina|bell miner]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1801|bell miner]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Bell miner\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704430/0 |title=''Manorina melanophrys'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| image = Bell Miner 1 - Nepean Weir.jpg\n| genus = Manorina\n| species = melanophrys\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1801)\n| range_map=Bell Miner Distribution From Atlas Living Australia.png\n| range_map_caption=Bell miner range<ref>{{cite web|title=Manorina (Manorina) melanophrys (Latham, 1801) Bell Miner|url=http://bie.ala.org.au/species/Manorina+%28Manorina%29+melanophrys#|website=Atlas of Living Australia|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''bell miner''' (''Manorina melanophrys''), commonly known as the '''bellbird''', is a colonial [[honeyeater]], endemic to southeastern [[Australia]].  The common name refers to their bell-like call. 'Miner' is an old alternative spelling of '[[myna]]', and is shared with other members of the genus ''[[Manorina]]''.<ref>For the derivation of 'miner' from 'myna', see comment at Common Indian Myna [http://fennerschool-associated.anu.edu.au/myna/] Retrieved 12 September 2013</ref>  The birds feed almost exclusively on the dome-like coverings, referred to as 'bell lerps', of certain [[psyllid]] bugs that feed on [[eucalyptus]] sap from the leaves. The psyllids make these bell lerps from their own honeydew secretions in order to protect themselves from predators and the environment.\n\nBell miners live in large, complex, social groups.  Within each group, there are subgroups consisting of several breeding pairs, but also including a number of birds that are not currently breeding.  The nonbreeders help in providing food for the young in all the nests within the subgroup, even though they are not necessarily closely related to them.<ref name=\"Ethology\">{{cite journal | last1 = Clarke | first1 = M. F. | year = 1989 | title = The pattern of helping in the bell miner (''Manorina melanophrys'') | doi = 10.1111/j.1439-0310.1989.tb00748.x | journal = Ethology | volume = 80 | issue = 1\u20134| pages = 292\u2013306 }}</ref>  The birds defend their colony area communally and aggressively, excluding most other [[passerine]] species.  They do this in order to protect their territory from other insect-eating birds that would eat the bell lerps on which they feed.  Whenever the local forests die back, due to increased lerp psyllid infestations, bell miners undergo a population boom.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe bell miner (''Manorina melanophrys'') belongs to the family of [[honeyeater]]s and Australian chats ([[Meliphagidae]]), which is part of the superfamily [[Meliphagoidea]] that also comprises the Australian warblers, scrubwrens, and thornbills ([[Acanthizidae]]); bristlebirds ([[Dasyornithidae]]); fairy-wrens ([[Maluridae]]); and pardalotes ([[Pardalotidae]]).<ref name=\"Phylogeny\">{{cite journal|last1=Gardner|first1=Janet L.|last2=Trueman|first2=John W.H.|last3=Ebert|first3=Daniel|last4=Joseph|first4=Leo|last5=Magrath|first5=Robert D.|title=Phylogeny and evolution of the Meliphagoidea, the largest radiation of Australasian songbirds|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|date=June 2010|volume=55|issue=3|pages=1087\u20131102|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2010.02.005|pmid=20152917}}</ref>\nBell miners share the genus ''[[Manorina]]'' with three other endemic Australian miners: the [[noisy miner]] (''M. melanocephala''), the [[yellow-throated miner]] (''M. flavigula''), and the endangered [[black-eared miner]] (''M. melanotis''). The three other miners were previously classified in the genus ''Myzantha'', which is still sometimes listed as a subgenus for those species. The closest related genus to ''[[Manorina]]'' has been genetically found to be the New Guinea and New Britain ''[[Melidectes]]'' honeyeaters. The bell miner's tinkling bell-like call was noted by early European explorers, <ref name=\"AustralianBirdNames\">{{cite book|last1=Fraser|first1=Ian|last2=Gray|first2=Jeannie|title=Australian bird names : a complete guide|date=2013|publisher=CSIRO Publishing|location=Collingwood, Vic.|isbn=9780643104693|page=204}}</ref> \nand the name bellbird was considered established 30 years later, when David Collins mentioned \"the melancholy cry of the bellbird.\"\n<ref name=\"AustralianBirdNames\" />\n<ref name=\"Collins\">{{cite book|last1=Collins|first1=David|title=An Account of the English Colony of New South Wales Volume 2|date=1802|location=London|url=http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks/e00011.html|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref>\nIn 1802, John [[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]] named the bird ''Turdus melanophrys'' meaning 'black-browed thrush'.<ref name=\"AustralianBirdNames\" /><ref name=\"Latham\">{{cite book|last1=Latham|first1=J|title=Supplementum Indicis Ornithologici sive Systematis Ornithologiae|publisher=Leigh & Sotheby|date=1848|location=London|url=http://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/en/fs1/object/display/bsb10483009_00001.html?leftTab=toc|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref> While Latham's scientific name became accepted, John Gould continued to use Australian bellbird as the name for the species in 1848.<ref name=\"AustralianBirdNames\" /><ref name=\"Gould\">{{cite book|last1=Gould|first1=John|title=The Birds of Australia Volume 1-7|date=1848|location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe common name of bellbird may lead to some confusion with the Australian inland endemic [[crested bellbird]], which is of the family [[Oreoicidae]]. The two species exhibit very different calls, behaviour, and do not overlap in range.<ref name=\"Pizzey\">{{cite book|last1=Pizzey|first1=Graham|last2=Knight|first2=Frank|title=The Field Guide to the Birds of Australia|edition=Ninth|date=2012|publisher=Harper Collins|location=Sydney|isbn=9780732299828}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nBell miners are the smallest of their genus, and differ from the other three predominantly grey miner species in having olive-green plumage, darker on the wings and yellower on the belly.<ref name=\"Officer\">{{cite book|last1=Stirling|first1=Hugh R. Officer ; ill. by Peg Maltby ; map by Alex|title=Australian honeyeaters|date=1971|publisher=Bird Observers Club|location=Melbourne|isbn=978-0-909711-03-0|page=71|edition=2dwith amendments and distribution maps.}}</ref>\nThey are a medium bodied honeyeater, slightly smaller and stockier than a [[Lewin's honeyeater]] (''Meliphaga lewinii''), weighing between 25g and 35g<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\">{{cite book|last1=Higgins|first1=P. J.|last2=Peter|first2=J. M.|last3=Steele|first3=W. K.|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand & Antarctic Birds Volume 5: Tyrant-flycatchers to ChatsTyrant flycatchers to chats|date=2001|publisher=Oxford Univ. Press|location=South Melbourne [u.a.]|isbn=978-0195532586|pages=609\u2013626}}</ref>\n(average 29g).<ref name=\"BirdInBackyards:BellMiner\">{{cite web|title=Bell Miner|url=http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/species/Manorina-melanophrys|website=Birds In Backyards|publisher=Birdlife Australia|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\nBell miners are 17.5\u201320&nbsp;cm in length (average 18.5&nbsp;cm) with a 22\u201330&nbsp;cm wingspan (average 26.5&nbsp;cm).<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\nThey have the characteristic yellow bill of the miners, which is slightly downturned. The legs are bright orange, and the bare patch behind the eye is red-orange.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\nThe crown and lores are black, while the feathers in front of the eye are yellow. A dark streak runs from the corner of the bill downward<ref name=\"Officer\" />\ngiving a slight frowning appearance. Eyes are brown and mouth is yellow.<ref name=\"BandersAid\">{{cite book|last1=Ken|first1=Rogers|last2=Rogers|first2=Annie|last3=Rogers|first3=Danny|title=Bander's aid : a guide to ageing and sexing bush birds|date=1986|publisher=A. Rogers|location=St. Andrews, Vic.|isbn=978-1862526402|pages=86\u201387|url=http://birdlife.org.au/documents/OTHPUB-Banders-Aid.pdf|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>\nBoth sexes look alike, though the males tend to be slightly larger.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\nIt is possible to determine the sex of the birds by analyzing wing length, tail length, and culmen depth, or by observing calls that are unique to females, but there is no easy way to reliably determine the sex in the field without careful observation of behaviour and calls.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=MF|last2=Heathcote|first2=CF|title=Methods for Sexing and Aging the Bell Miner Manorina melanophrys|journal=Emu|date=1988|volume=88|issue=2|pages=118|doi=10.1071/MU9880118}}</ref>\nJuveniles are more brown-colored than the adults and overall less bright in color. Young birds do not have the bare skin patch behind the eye. The patch initially develops as pale grey, then transforms to pale yellow, and darkens to pale orange before taking on the adult bright red-orange color as the bird matures.<ref name=\"BandersAid\" /><ref name=\"ABSA\">{{cite book|last1=Hardy|first1=J. W.|title=Bird in the Hand|edition=2nd|url=http://www.absa.asn.au/absainc/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bell-Miner.pdf|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>\nNestlings are born naked and develop light brown down about two days post hatching.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\n\nThe birds are heard more than they are seen, as bell miners tend to forage high in the [[Canopy (biology)|canopy]], and their olive-green plumage blends into the surrounding leaves. However, they keep up their \"ping\" contact call as they forage throughout the day.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> In the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Melbourne]], bell miners come low enough to be easily seen and photographed.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nBell miners are distributed from around [[Gympie]] in [[Queensland]], south along the coastal plain and ranges, to [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], around [[Melbourne]].<ref name=\"Officer\" /><ref name=\"HoneyeaterDistribution\">{{cite journal|last1=Gannon|first1=G.R.|title=Distribution of the Australian honeyeaters.|journal=Emu|date=1962|volume=62|issue=3|pages=145\u2013166|doi=10.1071/MU962145}}</ref>\nThey prefer the margins of wet or dry [[sclerophyll]] forest and thick woodlands, often with a stream or other permanent water source nearby.<ref name=\"NestEgg\">{{cite book|last1=Beruldsen|first1=Gordon|title=Australian birds their nests and eggs|date=2003|publisher=G. Beruldsen|location=Kenmore Hills, Qld.|isbn=978-0-646-42798-0|page=313|edition=rev.}}</ref>\nThis limits their range to higher rainfall areas near the coast, often bordering, but not inside, rainforest. Compared to the closely related noisy miner,<ref name =\"Birdlife\">{{cite book|last1=Rowley|first1=Ian|title=Bird life|date=1974|publisher=Collins|location=Sydney|isbn=978-0-00-211438-7|pages=119\u2013120}}</ref>\nbell miners prefer a denser habitat with a thick [[understory]] (<5 m), but a sparse midstory (5\u201315 m) and canopy (>15m).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lambert|first1=Kathryn T. A.|last2=Kumar|first2=Lalit|last3=Reid|first3=Nick|last4=McDonald|first4=Paul G.|title=Habitat selection by a despotic passerine, the Bell Miner (): When restoring habitat through Lantana () removal is not enough|journal=Ecological Management & Restoration|date=January 2016|volume=17|issue=1|pages=81\u201384|doi=10.1111/emr.12196}}</ref>\nIn an undisturbed setting, bell miners choose habitat with an understory of shrubs, ferns, sedges, and rainforest vines.<ref name=\"Thesis\">{{cite book|last1=Hastings|first1=Tony|title=Rainforests and Bell Miner Associated Dieback in Natural Ecosystems|date=May 2012|location=Charles Sturt University|page=85|url=http://www.tonyhastings.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/reports/hastings%20BMAD%20thesis.pdf|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref>\nThey have been observed to expand their range in disturbed habitats that have a thick undergrowth of the invasive weed [[lantana]].<ref name=\"LantanaMiners\">{{cite journal|last1=Somerville|first1=Susan|last2=Somerville|first2=Wayne|last3=Coyle|first3=Rodney|title=Regenerating native forest using splatter gun techniques to remove Lantana|journal=Ecological Management & Restoration|date=December 2011|volume=12|issue=3|pages=164\u2013174|doi=10.1111/j.1442-8903.2011.00608.x}}</ref>\nBell miner population densities have been measured at 14-38 birds per hectare.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kemmerer|first1=Ernst P.|last2=Shields|first2=Jim M.|last3=Tidemann|first3=Christopher R.|title=High densities of bell miners Manorina melanophrys associated with reduced diversity of other birds in wet eucalypt forest: Potential for adaptive management|journal=Forest Ecology and Management|date=April 2008|volume=255|issue=7|pages=2094\u20132102|doi=10.1016/j.foreco.2007.12.035}}</ref>\nThey are particular about their preferred habitat and reasonably small disturbances to undergrowth, such as fire or lantana removal, can cause a colony to move to a new territory.<ref name=\"NestEgg\" />\n\n==Behaviour==\n\n===Social organization===\nThe complex social organization of bell miners was observed as early as the 1960s<ref name=\"HoneyeaterDistribution\" /> in [[New South Wales]], and has been studied by several research groups in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\nBell miners live in large colonies of 8-200+ birds,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hyem|first1=E.L|title=Notes on the Birds of \"Mernot, \" Barrington, N.S.W.|journal=Emu|date=1936|volume=36|issue=4|pages=262\u2013272|doi=10.1071/MU936262}}</ref> \nwhich consist of coteries or clans of generally related male birds and their offspring. Each coterie is made up of several monogamous breeding pairs with their nest helpers.<ref name=\"GeneticStructure\">{{cite journal|last1=Painter|first1=J. N.|last2=Crozier|first2=R. H.|last3=Poiani|first3=A.|last4=Robertson|first4=R. J.|last5=Clarke|first5=M. F.|title=Complex social organization reflects genetic structure and relatedness in the cooperatively breeding bell miner, Manorina melanophrys|journal=Molecular Ecology|date=September 2000|volume=9|issue=9|pages=1339\u20131347|doi=10.1046/j.1365-294x.2000.01012.x}}</ref>\nAs a colony, bell miners are aggressive and set up a permanent territory that they will defend together against all other honeyeaters and any other species, which they perceive are a threat to their preferred food source or themselves.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" />\nWithin the colonial territory, each breeding pair has its own foraging range. Helpers assist multiple breeding pairs, and move between the foraging range of several pairs. Coteries are groups that are interconnected and interact daily within the larger colony, due to a close genetic relationship.<ref name=\"KinSelection\">{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=Michael F.|title=Co-operative Breeding by the Australian Bell Miner Manorina melanophrys Latham: A Test of Kin Selection Theory|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|date=1984|volume=14|issue=2|pages=137\u2013146|jstor=4599660|doi=10.1007/bf00291904}}</ref>\n\nDue to their aggressive nature, bell miners are known for excluding other birds from their territory, and larger avian species, like kookaburras, currawongs, and crows are mobbed by up to twelve miners from different coteries within the colony. Predators are repeatedly attacked, if they settle in another part of the colony's territory. Small birds that keep to the understory, like fairy wrens, scrub wrens and blackbirds are often not driven out,<ref name=\"SocialOrganization\">{{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=AJ|last2=Robertson|first2=BI|title=Social Organization of Bell Miners|journal=Emu|date=1978|volume=78|issue=4|pages=169|doi=10.1071/MU9780169}}</ref>\nbut small birds that typically forage in the midstory or canopy or share similar foods, like pardalotes, are not allowed access within the territory. One of the few species that can sometimes displace bell miners is the similarly aggressive noisy miner, but in general noisy miners prefer areas with little understory.<ref name=\"InterspeciesAggression\">{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=MF|title=Interspecific aggression within the Genus|journal=Emu|date=1984|volume=84|issue=2|pages=113\u2013115|doi=10.1071/MU9840113}}</ref>\nBell miners are able to suppress the numbers of competing species in territory that they hold for years.<ref name=\"AsymmetricalCompetition\">{{cite journal|last1=Poiani|first1=A.|last2=Rogers|first2=A.|last3=Rogers|first3=K.|last4=Rogers|first4=D.|title=Asymmetrical competition between the bell miner (Manorina melanophrys, Meliphagidae) and other honeyeaters: evidence from Southeastern Victoria, Australia|journal=Oecologia|date=December 1990|volume=85|issue=2|pages=250\u2013256|doi=10.1007/BF00319410|pmid=28312564}}</ref> \nHowever, bell miner colonies have clearly defined territorial boundaries, and beyond those boundaries the local bird assemblage resumes its normal diversity.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leseberg|first1=Nicholas P.|last2=Lambert|first2=Kathryn T. A.|last3=McDonald|first3=Paul G.|title=Fine-scale impacts on avian biodiversity due to a despotic species, the bell miner ()|journal=Austral Ecology|date=May 2015|volume=40|issue=3|pages=245\u2013254|doi=10.1111/aec.12206}}</ref>\n\n===Feeding===\nBell miners specialize in consuming insects known as [[Jumping plant louse|psyllid]]s and their associated young nymphs, sweet [[lerp (biology)|lerps]], and other psyllid secretions. Psyllid products may consist of up to 90% of the bell miner's diet.<ref name=\"LoynScience\">{{cite journal|last1=Loyn|first1=Richard H.|title=Territorial Bell Miners and Other Birds Affecting Populations of Insect Prey|journal=Science|date=September 30, 1983|volume=221|issue=4618|pages=1411\u20133|doi=10.1126/science.221.4618.1411|pmid=17759017}}</ref> Bell miners forage primarily among leaves, branches, and loose bark in the canopy, generally at least 8 m in height, but they do descend to the dense understory.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> There is a theory that bell miners 'farm' psyllids by excluding other psyllid-eating bird species from a large enough territory that the miners themselves do not require all the psyllids to sustain the colony.<ref name=\"FarmsDell\">{{cite journal|last1=Loyn|first1=Richard H.|title=The Bird that Farms the Dell|journal=Natural History (Pre-1988)|date=June 1987|volume=96|issue=6}}</ref> One hypothesis under the farming theory is that the bell miners may selectively eat only older nymphs or may often eat the lerps and leave the nymph unharmed.<ref name=\"FarmsDell\" /> Evidence for this theory has been mixed. An early study of stomach contents did not find supporting evidence for this theory, as miner stomachs did not contain the higher lerp/nymph ratio that would have been expected.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Poiani|first1=A|title=Bell Miners: What Kind of Farmers Are They?|journal=Emu|date=1993|volume=93|issue=3|pages=188\u2013194|doi=10.1071/MU9930188}}</ref> However, a later behavioral comparison between bell miners and noisy miners did observe that bell miners carefully used their tongue to remove lerps, which left the nymph intact. In contrast, noisy miners pried the lerp and nymph off with their beak and consumed both.<ref name=\"NonLethalForage\">{{cite journal|last1=HAYTHORPE|first1=KATHRYN M.|last2=McDONALD|first2=PAUL G.|title=Non-lethal foraging by bell miners on a herbivorous insect: Potential implications for forest health|journal=Austral Ecology|date=25 February 2010|volume=35|issue=4|pages=444\u2013450|doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.2009.02099.x}}</ref> When bell miners are removed, psyllid colonies are generally quickly decimated by the other forest bird species that move into the miners' former territory.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /><ref name=\"LoynScience\" />\n\nAlthough psyllids are the primary food source, like most honeyeaters bell miners have also been recorded drinking nectar from eucalyptus, banksia, and mistletoe flowers, as well as eating various other insects including spiders, beetles, weevils, moths and wasps.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /><ref name=\"Food\">{{cite book|last1=Barker|first1=R.D.|last2=Vestjens|first2=W.J.M.|title=The food of Australian birds|date=1989|publisher=CSIRO Division of Wildlife and Ecology|location=Lyneham, A.C.T.|isbn=978-0643051157|pages=196\u2013197}}</ref>\n\n====Bell Miner Associated Dieback====\nBell miners are so closely associated with eucalyptus dieback that the phenomenon has been named Bell Miner Associated Dieback (BMAD). Concern about BMAD has led to the formation of the BMAD Working Group,<ref name=\"WorkingGroup\">{{cite web|title=Bell Miner Associated Dieback Working Group|url=http://www.bmad.com.au/workinggroup.php|website=Bell Miner Associated Dieback|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> the 2004 BMAD Strategy,<ref name=\"Strategy\">{{cite book|title=Bell Miner Associated Dieback Strategy 2004|date=2004|publisher=Bell Miner Associated Dieback Working Group|pages=1\u201319|url=http://www.bmad.com.au/publications/BMAD_Strategy_2004.pdf|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> the 2005 BMAD National Forum,<ref name=\"NationalForum\">{{cite book|title=Proceedings of the Bell Miner Associated Dieback National Forum|date=March 30, 2005|location=Southern Cross University, Lismore, Australia|url=http://www.bmad.com.au/publications/BMAD_Proceedings.pdf|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> the 2006 BMAD Literature Review,<ref name=\"LitReview\">{{cite book|last1=Wardell-Johnson|first1=Grant|last2=Stone|first2=Christine|last3=Recher|first3=Harry|last4=Lynch|first4=A. Jasmyn J.|title=Bell miner associated dieback (BMAD) independent scientific literature review : a review of eucalypt dieback associated with Bell miner habitat in north-eastern New South Wales, Australia|date=2006|publisher=Dept. of Environment and Conservation (NSW)|location=[Coffs Harbour, N.S.W.]|isbn=978-1741378566|url=http://www.bmad.com.au/publications/LiteratureReview.pdf|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> and continues to be an area of active research. Eucalyptus dieback involved complicated ecosystems with numerous variables and occurs in some habitats without the presence of bell miners,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Jurskis|first1=Vic|title=Eucalypt decline in Australia, and a general concept of tree decline and dieback|journal=Forest Ecology and Management|date=August 2005|volume=215|issue=1\u20133|pages=1\u201320|doi=10.1016/j.foreco.2005.04.026}}</ref> but there is a high correlation with bell miner presence and eucalyptus dieback that was noted as early as 1982. One theory is that the monopolising and/or farming of psyllids by bell miners allows psyllid numbers to build up, eventually leading to tree sickness and possibly death.<ref name=\"SurveyCrownDieback\">{{cite book|last1=Stone|first1=C.|last2=Spolc|first2=D.|last3=Urquhart|first3=C.A.|title=Survey of crown dieback in moist hardwood forests in the central and northern regions of New South Wales state forests (psyllid/bell miner research programme)|date=1995|publisher=Research Division, State Forests of New South Wales|location=Sydney|isbn=978-0731022168}}</ref> In some cases where bell miners have been removed the avian diversity has been restored and the psyllid infestation reduced to the point of trees returning to health.<ref name=\"LoynScience\" /> However, in other studies the trees did not recover even after bell miner removal, so more research is needed to better understand the relationship between bell miners and eucalyptus dieback.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=Michael F|last2=Schedvin|first2=Natasha|title=Removal of bell miners Manorina melanophrys from Eucalyptus radiata forest and its effect on avian diversity, psyllids and tree health|journal=Biological Conservation|date=April 1999|volume=88|issue=1|pages=111\u2013120|doi=10.1016/S0006-3207(98)00083-4}}</ref>\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:BabyBellMiner1.jpg|thumb|right|immature birds]]\nBell miners are generally sedentary and thus have a permanent all-purpose territory which includes breeding. The primary breeding season is April/May to August/September in the northern part of their range and June/July to November/December in the southern range,<ref name=\"NestEgg\" /> but breeding has been observed in all months of the year<ref name=\"SocialOrganization\" /><ref name=\"ReproductiveBehavior\">{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=MF|title=The Reproductive Behavior of the Bell Miner|journal=Emu|date=1988|volume=88|issue=2|pages=88\u2013100|doi=10.1071/MU9880088}}</ref> as females will often nest again after a failed nest or once the young have fledged. One female was recorded nesting five times in one season, though that many nest attempts is unusual.<ref name=\"SocialOrganization\" /> Bell miner pairs are monogamous, but the breeding tasks are divided between the sexes. Female bell miners build the nest over 8 days, incubate the 1-3 (but typically 2) eggs for 14.5 days, and brood the young for up to 12 days depending on the weather.<ref name=\"ReproductiveBehavior\" /> The nests are small, cup-shaped and built with dry twigs, grasses, and bark woven together with spider web.<ref name=\"NestEgg\" /> Nests are generally hidden in the foliage of dense understory plants, 3-5m above the ground.<ref name=\"NestEgg\" /> The eggs are typically 24mm x 16mm, oval shaped, and pink in color. They have darker reddish brown spots and blotches primarily over the larger end.<ref name=\"NestEgg\" /> Pallid cuckoos have been recorded as nest parasites for bell miners.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Swainson|first1=G.W.|title=Co-operative rearing in the Bell Miner|journal=Emu|date=1970|volume=70|issue=4|pages=183\u2013188|doi=10.1071/MU970183}}</ref>\n\nWhile nests are all within the territory of the colony, they are not tightly packed as traditional colony breeders. Instead nests are located within the breeding pairs' normal foraging range. They are generally within calling range of neighbour nests, but not too close.<ref name=\"SpacialOrg\">{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=MF|last2=Fitzgerald|first2=GF|title=Spatial-Organization of the Cooperatively Breeding Bell Miner|journal=Emu|date=1994|volume=94|issue=2|pages=96|doi=10.1071/MU9940096}}</ref> Female bell miners move nest locations after a nest failure and were observed to move nests lower into the thick understory, likely reducing the risk of avian predators. However, they did not move nests far from the original location horizontally, possibly to stay within their home foraging range and to retain their established set of helpers.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Beckmann|first1=Christa|last2=McDonald|first2=Paul G.|title=Placement of Re-nests Following Predation: Are Birds Managing Risk?|journal=Emu|date=2016|volume=116|pages=9\u201313|doi=10.1071/mu15064}}</ref> Females will also alter brood sex ratios to meet conditions. When a colony is in a new location with an inferior food source the ratio will be biased towards more females which will disperse from the colony at sexual maturity. Once the food supply has been increased, the brood sex ratio is shifted towards future helping males.<ref name=\"BroodSexRatio\">{{cite journal|last1=Ewen|first1=J. G.|title=Facultative control of offspring sex in the cooperatively breeding bell miner, Manorina melanophrys|journal=Behavioral Ecology|date=1 March 2003|volume=14|issue=2|pages=157\u2013164|doi=10.1093/beheco/14.2.157}}</ref>\n\n====Nest helpers====\nBoth parents and helpers provision and care for the nestlings. Nests may be attended by up to 20 helpers,<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> and nest success has been observed to be higher when there are at least 6 additional helpers attending the nest in addition to the breeding pair.<ref name=\"Ethology\" /> Helpers feed the young, defend the nest against predators, remove droppings, and remove parasites.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> Nest helpers include both sexes, but are predominately young and breeding age males. Juvenile birds start helping as early as 1.3 months old.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> Older non-breeding males contribute the most food to nestlings and assist with multiple nests.<ref name=\"Ethology\" /> The amount of help offered by a nest helper is correlated with its genetic relationship with the nestlings it is feeding.<ref name=\"KinSelection\" /> Bell miners use a provisioning call when they arrive at the nest to stimulate the young to beg. Provisioning calls are similar among closely related miners, so helpers preferentially help young with fathers which have provisioning calls similar to their own.\n<ref name=\"BeggingCalls\">{{cite journal|last1=McDonald|first1=P. G.|last2=Wright|first2=J.|title=Bell miner provisioning calls are more similar among relatives and are used by helpers at the nest to bias their effort towards kin|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences|date=30 March 2011|volume=278|issue=1723|pages=3403\u20133411|doi=10.1098/rspb.2011.0307|pmid=21450738|pmc=3177633}}</ref>\nHowever, it is important to note that even non-related helpers have been shown to contribute a significant amount to raising young,\n<ref name=\"NonRelatedHelpers\">{{cite journal|last1=Wright|first1=J.|last2=McDonald|first2=P. G.|last3=te Marvelde|first3=L.|last4=Kazem|first4=A. J. N.|last5=Bishop|first5=C. M.|title=Helping effort increases with relatedness in bell miners, but 'unrelated' helpers of both sexes still provide substantial care|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences|date=21 October 2009|volume=277|issue=1680|pages=437\u2013445|doi=10.1098/rspb.2009.1360|pmid=19846458|pmc=2842640}}</ref>\nand no difference was seen in the amount of help offered by helpers depending on the brood sex even though male chicks tend to stay with the colony and become helpers while females disperse.\n<ref>{{cite journal|last1=McDonald|first1=Paul G.|last2=Ewen|first2=John G.|last3=Wright|first3=Jonathan|title=Brood sex ratio does not affect helper effort in a cooperative bird, despite extreme sex-biased dispersal|journal=Animal Behaviour|date=January 2010|volume=79|issue=1|pages=243\u2013250|doi=10.1016/j.anbehav.2009.11.007}}</ref> \nHelpers will delay bringing food to the nestlings when the female is brooding them, but will eventually bring food even if the female continues to brood. The brooding female is more likely to allow the young to be fed if the attendant is her mate.<ref name=\"BroodingBehavior\">{{cite journal|last1=Archard|first1=G.A.|last2=Robertson|first2=R.J.|last3=Jones|first3=D.|last4=Painter|first4=J.|last5=Crozier|first5=R.|last6=Clarke|first6=M.F.|title=Brooding behaviour in the cooperatively breeding Bell Miner (Manorina melanophrys)|journal=Emu|date=1 January 2006|volume=106|issue=2|pages=105\u2013112|doi=10.1071/mu05032}}</ref>\n\n====Fledgling to adulthood====\nYoung bell miners leave the nest about 12 days post hatching, but continue to be fed by parents and helpers for a further 10 weeks.<ref name=\"ReproductiveBehavior\" /> Bell miners will start helping at nests when less than 2 months old, but the transition is gradual such that recently fledged birds will continue to beg from other helpers, and then either consume the offered food or give it to younger birds.<ref name=\"KinSelection\" /> Females tend to disperse from the colony at 8 months and they reach breeding age at 8.3 months. It is likely that as they reach maturity the mothers become intolerant of their mature daughters prompting their dispersal. The mortality of bell miners prior to breeding age is very high at 93%.<ref name=\"Dispersal\">{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=MF|last2=Heathcote|first2=CF|title=Dispersal, Survivorship and Demography in the Co-Operatively-Breeding Bell Miner|journal=Emu|date=1990|volume=90|issue=1|pages=15|doi=10.1071/MU9900015}}</ref> The greatest risk is soon after young bell miners leave the nest when many are preyed upon.<ref name=\"SocialOrganization\" /> Known predators include grey currawong, Australian raven, laughing kookaburra, brown goshawk, copperhead snake, and eastern brown snake.<ref name=\"HANZAB:Honeyeaters\" /> By the time they reach breeding age the sex ratio is skewed with more surviving males, probably due to higher mortality of the dispersing females.<ref name=\"Dispersal\" />\n\n[[Image:Bell Miner boulumba1.ogg|thumb|300px|left|Bouloumba Creek, SE Queensland, Australia]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Manorina melanophrys}}\n{{Wikispecies|Manorina melanophrys}}\n* Bell Miner Associated Dieback [http://www.bmad.com.au/publications.html]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3179448}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:miner, bell}}\n[[Category:Manorina|bell miner]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1801|bell miner]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSocial organization:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bell_miner"}
{"title_page": "Nilton Terroso", "text_new": "{{short description|French football coach and former player}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Nilton Terroso\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Nilton dos Santos Terroso\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|9|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = France\n| height = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = 1995\u20131997 | youthclubs1 = [[S.C. Lourinhanense|Lourinhanense]]\n| years1 = 1997\u20132001 | clubs1 = [[S.C. Lourinhanense|Lourinhanense]] | caps1 = 84 | goals1 = 5 \n| years2 = 2001 | clubs2 = Sans Souci | caps2 = | goals2 = \n| years3 = 2002\u20132004 | clubs3 = Riachense | caps3 = | goals3 =\n| years4 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs4 = [[S.C. Lourinhanense|Lourinhanense]] | caps4 = | goals4 =\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 1995 | nationalteam1 = Canada U15 | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 =\n| nationalyears2 = 1995 | nationalteam2 = [[Canada men's national under-17 soccer team|Canada U17]] | nationalcaps2 = | nationalgoals2 =\n| nationalyears3 = 2001 | nationalteam3 = [[Canada men's national under-23 soccer team|Canada U23]] | nationalcaps3 = 1 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2011\u20132013 | managerclubs1 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2016 | managerclubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Clube de Portugal|Atl\u00e9tico]]\n| manageryears3 = 2017\u20132018 | managerclubs3 = [[S.C. Olhanense|Olhanense]]\n| club-update =\n}}\n'''Nilton dos Santos Terroso''' (born 13 September 1979) is a former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]], and is a [[Manager (association football)|coach]].\n\n==Early life==\nTerroso was born in France and grew up in [[Prince George, British Columbia]], Canada. He represented [[Canada men's national soccer team|the latter nation]] at three age-group levels.<ref name=Analysis>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/analysis-meet-man-whose-appliance-2034903|title=Analysis: Meet the man whose appliance of science could push Cardiff City to promotion|publisher=[[Media Wales#WalesOnline|WalesOnline]]|author=Terry Phillips|date=26 March 2013|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nHaving moved to Portugal still in his formative years, Terroso never competed in higher than the [[Portuguese Second Division]] as a senior. He had two spells at [[S.C. Lourinhanense]] ([[Sporting CP]]'s [[farm team]], where he played alongside [[Sim\u00e3o Sabrosa]]), and also represented Clube Atl\u00e9tico Riachense.<ref name=SAPO>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/segunda-liga/artigos/treinador-nilton-terroso-quer-futebol-atrativo-no-atletico|title=Treinador Nilton Terroso quer futebol atrativo no Atl\u00e9tico{{sic|nolink=y|\"}}|trans-title=Coach Nilton Terroso wants attractive football at Atl\u00e9tico|publisher=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|language=pt|date=2 March 2016|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nIn 2007, Terroso joined [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] as youth team fitness coach. Two years later, he was appointed assistant manager of their under-18 side, and worked with them for two years.<ref name=Interview>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lMTIkdhzmAo|title=Pre-season highlights: Nilton Terroso interview|publisher=Cardiff City F.C|via=[[YouTube]]|date=16 July 2014|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> \n\nStarting in 2010, Terroso acted as fitness coach to the [[Wales national under-17 football team|Welsh under-17s]] during one year. Subsequently, he joined [[Malky Mackay]]'s staff at Cardiff City's first team in the English [[EFL Championship|Championship]], still being his assistant when the club promoted to the [[Premier League]] at the end of the [[2012\u201313 Football League Championship|2012\u201313 season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.pt/internacional/detalhe/o-cientista-portugues-753275|title=O cientista portugu\u00eas|trans-title=The Portuguese scientist|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=25 April 2012|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/apr/17/cardiff-celebrate-promotion-premier-league|title='We've finally done it' \u2013 Cardiff celebrate promotion to Premier League|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|author=Stuart James|date=17 April 2013|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sulinformacao.pt/2017/11/nilton-terroso-e-o-novo-treinador-do-olhanense/|title=Nilton Terroso \u00e9 o novo treinador do Olhanense|trans-title=Nilton Terroso is the new manager of Olhanense|publisher=Sul Informa\u00e7\u00e3o|language=pt|date=17 November 2017|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn June 2014, Terroso was named head coach of Cardiff's under-21 team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/news/2014/july/terroso-immensely-proud-after-sarajevo-trip/|title=Terroso 'immensely proud' after Sarajevo trip|publisher=Cardiff City F.C|date=15 July 2014|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/who-jazzi-barnum-bobb-meet-cardiff-7611818|title=Who is Jazzi Barnum-Bobb? Meet the Cardiff City star with a brilliant name and bright future|publisher=WalesOnline|author=Terry Phillips|date=14 August 2014|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/cardiff-city-appoint-kevin-nicholson-8610390|title=Cardiff City appoint Kevin Nicholson as under-21 boss following Quinton Fortune exit|publisher=WalesOnline|author=Terry Phillips|date=9 February 2015|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=Interview/> At the end of [[2014\u201315 Cardiff City F.C. season|the campaign]], he left.\n\nOn 1 March 2016, 11 years after he last set foot in the country,<ref name=SAPO/> Terroso returned to Portugal and was appointed at [[LigaPro]] club [[Atl\u00e9tico Clube de Portugal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/ii-liga/tapadinha/atletico-luso-canadiano-nilton-terroso-sucede-e-pedro-hipolito-e-jorge-andrade|title=Atl\u00e9tico: luso-canadiano Nilton Terroso sucede a Pedro Hip\u00f3lito e Jorge Andrade|trans-title=Atl\u00e9tico: Portuguese-Canadian Nilton Terroso succeeds Pedro Hip\u00f3lito and Jorge Andrade|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref> After not being able to [[2015\u201316 LigaPro|prevent relegation]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/2a-liga/noticias/interior/atletico-perde-em-casa-com-oriental-e-desce-de-divisao-5174632.html|title=Atl\u00e9tico perde em casa com Oriental e desce de divis\u00e3o|trans-title=Atl\u00e9tico lose at home to Oriental and are relegated|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|language=pt|date=14 May 2016|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref> he left.\n\nTerroso signed as manager of [[S.C. Olhanense]] from the [[Campeonato de Portugal (league)|Campeonato de Portugal]] on 17 November 2017, succeeding [[Bruno Saraiva]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/campeonato-de-portugal/detalhe/olhanense-nilton-terroso-sucede-a-bruno-saraiva|title=Olhanense: Nilton Terroso sucede a Bruno Saraiva|trans-title=Olhanense: Nilton Terroso succeeds Bruno Saraiva|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=17 November 2017|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://portugalresident.com/new-coach-at-olhanense|title=New coach at Olhanense|publisher=Portugal Resident|date=20 November 2017|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTerroso is a qualified [[UEFA]] B licence coach, having completed a degree in football coaching and performance plus [[sports science]].<ref name=Analysis/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.glam.ac.uk/news/en/2011/sep/30/glamorgan-graduate-scores-top-job-cardiff-city-foo/|title=Glamorgan graduate scores top job with Cardiff City Football Club|publisher=[[University of South Wales]]|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo|197909130003}}\n*{{ForaDeJogo manager|10636}}\n*[https://canadasoccer.com/?pid=3144&t=profile Canada Soccer profile]\n*{{soccerway coach|nilton-dos-santos-terroso/437895}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terroso, Nilton}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Second Division players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese football managers]]\n[[Category:LigaPro managers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Clube de Portugal managers]]\n[[Category:S.C. Olhanense managers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Wales]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. non-playing staff]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French football coach and former player}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Nilton Terroso\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Nilton dos Santos Terroso\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|9|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = France\n| height = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = 1995\u20131997 | youthclubs1 = [[S.C. Lourinhanense|Lourinhanense]]\n| years1 = 1997\u20132001 | clubs1 = [[S.C. Lourinhanense|Lourinhanense]] | caps1 = 84 | goals1 = 5 \n| years2 = 2001 | clubs2 = Sans Souci | caps2 = | goals2 = \n| years3 = 2002\u20132004 | clubs3 = Riachense | caps3 = | goals3 =\n| years4 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs4 = [[S.C. Lourinhanense|Lourinhanense]] | caps4 = | goals4 =\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 1995 | nationalteam1 = Canada U15 | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 =\n| nationalyears2 = 1995 | nationalteam2 = [[Canada men's national under-17 soccer team|Canada U17]] | nationalcaps2 = | nationalgoals2 =\n| nationalyears3 = 2001 | nationalteam3 = [[Canada men's national under-23 soccer team|Canada U23]] | nationalcaps3 = 1 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2011\u20132013 | managerclubs1 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2016 | managerclubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Clube de Portugal|Atl\u00e9tico]]\n| manageryears3 = 2017\u20132018 | managerclubs3 = [[S.C. Olhanense|Olhanense]]\n| club-update =\n}}\n'''Nilton dos Santos Terroso''' (born 13 September 1979) is a former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]], and is a [[Manager (association football)|coach]].\n\n==Early life==\nTerroso was born in France and grew up in [[Prince George, British Columbia]], Canada. He represented [[Canada men's national soccer team|the latter nation]] at three age-group levels.<ref name=Analysis>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/analysis-meet-man-whose-appliance-2034903|title=Analysis: Meet the man whose appliance of science could push Cardiff City to promotion|publisher=[[Media Wales#WalesOnline|WalesOnline]]|author=Terry Phillips|date=26 March 2013|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nHaving moved to Portugal still in his formative years, Terroso never competed in higher than the [[Portuguese Second Division]] as a senior. He had two spells at [[S.C. Lourinhanense]] ([[Sporting CP]]'s [[farm team]], where he played alongside [[Sim\u00e3o Sabrosa]]), and also represented Clube Atl\u00e9tico Riachense.<ref name=SAPO>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/segunda-liga/artigos/treinador-nilton-terroso-quer-futebol-atrativo-no-atletico|title=Treinador Nilton Terroso quer futebol atrativo no Atl\u00e9tico{{sic|nolink=y|\"}}|trans-title=Coach Nilton Terroso wants attractive football at Atl\u00e9tico|publisher=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|language=pt|date=2 March 2016|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nIn 2007, Terroso joined [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] as youth team fitness coach. Two years later, he was appointed assistant manager of their under-18 side, and worked with them for two years.<ref name=Interview>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lMTIkdhzmAo|title=Pre-season highlights: Nilton Terroso interview|publisher=Cardiff City F.C|via=[[YouTube]]|date=16 July 2014|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> \n\nStarting in 2010, Terroso acted as fitness coach to the [[Wales national under-17 football team|Welsh under-17s]] during one year. Subsequently, he joined [[Malky Mackay]]'s staff at Cardiff City's first team in the English [[EFL Championship|Championship]], still being his assistant when the club promoted to the [[Premier League]] at the end of the [[2012\u201313 Football League Championship|2012\u201313 season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.pt/internacional/detalhe/o-cientista-portugues-753275|title=O cientista portugu\u00eas|trans-title=The Portuguese scientist|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=25 April 2012|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/apr/17/cardiff-celebrate-promotion-premier-league|title='We've finally done it' \u2013 Cardiff celebrate promotion to Premier League|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|author=Stuart James|date=17 April 2013|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sulinformacao.pt/2017/11/nilton-terroso-e-o-novo-treinador-do-olhanense/|title=Nilton Terroso \u00e9 o novo treinador do Olhanense|trans-title=Nilton Terroso is the new manager of Olhanense|publisher=Sul Informa\u00e7\u00e3o|language=pt|date=17 November 2017|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn June 2014, Terroso was named head coach of Cardiff's under-21 team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/news/2014/july/terroso-immensely-proud-after-sarajevo-trip/|title=Terroso 'immensely proud' after Sarajevo trip|publisher=Cardiff City F.C|date=15 July 2014|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/who-jazzi-barnum-bobb-meet-cardiff-7611818|title=Who is Jazzi Barnum-Bobb? Meet the Cardiff City star with a brilliant name and bright future|publisher=WalesOnline|author=Terry Phillips|date=14 August 2014|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/cardiff-city-appoint-kevin-nicholson-8610390|title=Cardiff City appoint Kevin Nicholson as under-21 boss following Quinton Fortune exit|publisher=WalesOnline|author=Terry Phillips|date=9 February 2015|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=Interview/> At the end of [[2014\u201315 Cardiff City F.C. season|the campaign]], he left.\n\nOn 1 March 2016, 11 years after he last set foot in the country,<ref name=SAPO/> Terroso returned to Portugal and was appointed at [[LigaPro]] club [[Atl\u00e9tico Clube de Portugal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/ii-liga/tapadinha/atletico-luso-canadiano-nilton-terroso-sucede-e-pedro-hipolito-e-jorge-andrade|title=Atl\u00e9tico: luso-canadiano Nilton Terroso sucede a Pedro Hip\u00f3lito e Jorge Andrade|trans-title=Atl\u00e9tico: Portuguese-Canadian Nilton Terroso succeeds Pedro Hip\u00f3lito and Jorge Andrade|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref> After not being able to [[2015\u201316 LigaPro|prevent relegation]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/2a-liga/noticias/interior/atletico-perde-em-casa-com-oriental-e-desce-de-divisao-5174632.html|title=Atl\u00e9tico perde em casa com Oriental e desce de divis\u00e3o|trans-title=Atl\u00e9tico lose at home to Oriental and are relegated|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|language=pt|date=14 May 2016|accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref> he left.\n\nTerroso signed as manager of [[S.C. Olhanense]] from the [[Campeonato de Portugal (league)|Campeonato de Portugal]] on 17 November 2017, succeeding [[Bruno Saraiva]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/campeonato-de-portugal/detalhe/olhanense-nilton-terroso-sucede-a-bruno-saraiva|title=Olhanense: Nilton Terroso sucede a Bruno Saraiva|trans-title=Olhanense: Nilton Terroso succeeds Bruno Saraiva|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=17 November 2017|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://portugalresident.com/new-coach-at-olhanense|title=New coach at Olhanense|publisher=Portugal Resident|date=20 November 2017|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTerroso is a qualified [[UEFA]] B licence coach, having completed a degree in football coaching and performance plus [[sports science]].<ref name=Analysis/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.glam.ac.uk/news/en/2011/sep/30/glamorgan-graduate-scores-top-job-cardiff-city-foo/|title=Glamorgan graduate scores top job with Cardiff City Football Club|publisher=[[University of South Wales]]|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo|197909130003}}\n*{{ForaDeJogo manager|10636}}\n*[https://canadasoccer.com/?pid=3144&t=profile Canada Soccer profile]\n*{{soccerway coach|nilton-dos-santos-terroso/437895}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terroso, Nilton}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Second Division players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese football managers]]\n[[Category:LigaPro managers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Clube de Portugal managers]]\n[[Category:S.C. Olhanense managers]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Wales]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. non-playing staff]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Even further.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nilton_Terroso"}
{"title_page": "Jim McMahon", "text_new": "{{About||the British politician|Jim McMahon (politician)}}\n{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|image=Jim McMahon (cropped).jpg\n|caption=McMahon at [[Hanscom Air Force Base]]<br>in [[Massachusetts]] in 1988\n|image_size=275\n|position=[[Quarterback]]\n|number=9\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1959|8|21}}\n|birth_place=[[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]], [[New Jersey]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place= \n|high_school = [[Roy High School (Utah)|Roy (UT)]]\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 1\n|weight_lbs = 195\n|draftyear=1982\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=5\n|college=[[BYU Cougars football|BYU]]\n|pastteams=\n* [[Chicago Bears]] ([[1982 NFL season|1982]]\u2013[[1988 NFL season|1988]])\n* [[San Diego Chargers]] ([[1989 NFL season|1989]])\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ([[1990 NFL season|1990]]\u2013[[1992 NFL season|1992]])\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ([[1993 NFL season|1993]])\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] ([[1994 NFL season|1994]])\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ([[1995 NFL season|1995]])*\n* [[Green Bay Packers]] ([[1995 NFL season|1995]]\u2013[[1996 NFL season|1996]])\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|statlabel1= Games Played\n|statvalue1= 119\n|statlabel2= Games Started\n|statvalue2= 97\n|statlabel3=[[Touchdown|TD]]s\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n|statvalue3=100\u201390\n|statlabel4=Yards\n|statvalue4=18,148\n|statlabel5=[[Passer rating|QB Rating]]\n|statvalue5=78.2\n|nfl=MCM166115\n|highlights=\n'''NCAA'''\n* 2\u00d7 Holiday Bowl MVP\n* 2\u00d7 [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[1980 College Football All-America Team|1980]], [[1981 College Football All-America Team|1981]])\n* 1981 [[Davey O'Brien Award]] winner\n* 1981 [[Sammy Baugh Trophy]] winner\n* [[BYU Cougars football|BYU Cougars #9 retired]]\n'''NFL'''\n* [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1986 Pro Bowl|1985]])\n* [[United Press International|UPI]] 2nd-Team All-NFC (1985)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XX|XX]], [[Super Bowl XXXI|XXXI]])\n* [[Brian Piccolo Award]] (1982)\n* [[UPI NFL-NFC Rookie of the Year|''UPI'' NFC Rookie of the Year]] (1982)\n* [[National Football League Comeback Player of the Year Award#PFW/PFWA Comeback Player of the Year award (1972\u2013present)|''PFW'' NFL Comeback Player of the Year]] (1991)\n|CollegeHOF=2043\n|name=Jim McMahon\n|}}\n'''James Robert McMahon Jr.''' (born August 21, 1959) is an American former [[American football|football]] player. He played [[college football]] at [[Brigham Young University]], where he was a two-time All-American ([[1980 College Football All-America Team|1980]], [[1981 College Football All-America Team|1981]]) and later in the professional ranks with the [[Chicago Bears]], [[San Diego Chargers]], [[Philadelphia Eagles]], [[Minnesota Vikings]], [[Arizona Cardinals]], [[Cleveland Browns]], and [[Green Bay Packers]].\n\nHe won two Super Bowl titles, the first with the Bears in [[Super Bowl XX]] where he was the starting quarterback, and the second with their rivals, the Green Bay Packers, in [[Super Bowl XXXI]] where he was a backup to [[Brett Favre]]. Both Super Bowls were against the [[New England Patriots]]. McMahon was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 1998.\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]], [[New Jersey]], McMahon moved with his family to [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]] when he was three.<ref name=\"ESPN Classic\" /> He played high school football his freshman and sophomore years at [[Andrew Hill High School]] in San Jose, then moved with his family in the summer of 1975 to [[Roy, Utah]]. He played his junior and senior years at [[Roy High School (Utah)|Roy High School]] and graduated in 1977.<ref name=\"ESPN Classic\">{{cite web|last=Carter|first=Bob|title=McMahon was a rebel without pause|url=http://espn.go.com/classic/biography/s/McMahon_Jim.html|publisher=ESPN Classic|accessdate=July 1, 2011|year=2007}}</ref><ref name=rbanaa>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=r9BSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KX8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5962%2C4783960 |work=Deseret News |location=(Salt Lake City, Utah) |last=Blodgett |first=Gary R. |title=Roy back an All-American |date=December 15, 1976 |page=6D}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nMcMahon mainly served as [[BYU]]'s punter during his [[1977 BYU Cougars football team|freshman season]]. Also he played baseball (1977), but he played enough at quarterback to throw his first-ever collegiate touchdown pass against [[UTEP Miners football|UTEP]]. He continued as the Cougars' punter as the [[1978 BYU Cougars football team|1978]] season began, but when [[Marc Wilson (American football)|Marc Wilson]] was injured in the third game of the season (against [[Colorado State Rams football|Colorado State]]), McMahon became the starting quarterback. McMahon led BYU to victory against CSU, accounting for 112 passing yards, 80 rushing yards, and two touchdowns. He was named Chevrolet Player of the Game and [[Western Athletic Conference|WAC]] Player of the Week for his performance. McMahon and Wilson shared quarterback duties for the rest of the season; McMahon played well enough to earn All-WAC honors and [[Associated Press]] Honorable Mention [[All-America]]. The best game of his sophomore year was against [[Wyoming Cowboys football|Wyoming]]: he passed for 317 yards and rushed for 49 more yards, earning another WAC Player of the Week award.\n\nMcMahon had suffered a knee injury towards the end of the 1978 season and BYU coaches chose to [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] him in [[1979 BYU Cougars football team|1979]]. McMahon watched from the sidelines as Wilson set nine [[NCAA]] records, tied two others, and became the first BYU player to earn consensus first team [[1979 College Football All-America Team|All-American]] honors; he finished third in [[Heisman Trophy]] [[1979 NCAA Division I-A football season#Heisman Trophy|balloting]].\n\nWith Wilson graduated and in the [[1980 NFL season|NFL]] with the [[1980 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], McMahon beat out Royce Bybee to claim the starting quarterback position in [[1980 BYU Cougars football team|1980]]. BYU lost the opener 25\u201321 against [[New Mexico Lobos football|New Mexico]], but then won eleven straight to claim the WAC championship. McMahon set 32 NCAA records, including single-season records for yards of total offense (4,627), passing yards (4,571), touchdown passes (47), and passing efficiency (176.9). His best game was against [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]]; he completed 21 of 33 passes for 485 yards and six touchdowns, and added two rushing touchdowns. That performance earned him ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'''s National Player of the Week award. McMahon's season statistics might have been even better, but he spent significant time on the sidelines because the Cougars won many games by wide margins. Although he started all 12 regular season games, he only finished three of them.\n\nBYU led the nation in passing offense, total offense, and scoring offense during the regular season. McMahon earned numerous awards for his individual accomplishments, being named WAC Player of the Year, unanimous First Team All-WAC, Utah Sportsman of the Year, and [[Deseret News]] Athlete of the Year. He was named to four All-America teams and finished fifth in Heisman Trophy voting.\n\nIn the [[1980 Holiday Bowl|Holiday Bowl]], the Cougars faced an [[1980 SMU Mustangs football team|SMU]] team led by star running backs [[Craig James (running back)|Craig James]] and [[Eric Dickerson]], and the Mustangs built a 45\u201325 lead over BYU with just four minutes left in the game. As Cougar fans headed for the exits, McMahon screamed that the game was not over yet. He guided BYU's offense to three quick touchdowns, including a 41-yard [[Hail Mary pass]] to Clay Brown to win the game<ref name=\"rock20100904\">{{cite news|last=Rock|first=Brad|title= Jim McMahon forever BYU's favorite rebel|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/print/700062850/Jim-McMahon-forever-BYUs-favorite-rebel.html|accessdate=September 4, 2010|newspaper=Deseret News|date=September 4, 2010}}</ref> as time expired. It is regarded as one of the greatest comebacks in college football history;<ref name=\"30for30\">\"SMU fell to BYU as quarterback Jim McMahon engineered what many dubbed 'the greatest comeback in college football bowl history'.\" Duffy, Patrick (narrator). \"Pony Excess\", ''[[30 for 30]]''. ESPN, November 11, 2010.</ref> BYU fans refer to it as the \"Miracle Bowl\".\n\nIn McMahon's senior season in [[1981 BYU Cougars football team|1981]], despite missing two games due to injuries, he passed for 3,555 yards and 30 touchdowns in the regular season, again leading BYU to a WAC championship. For his efforts, he was named WAC Player of the Year and unanimous First Team All-WAC. On a national level, he was named [[1981 College Football All-America Team|First-team All-American]] by five different organizations and finished third in Heisman Trophy balloting. He received the [[Davey O'Brien]] Trophy and the [[Sammy Baugh]] Award, and he shared the Pigskin Club NCAA Offensive Player of the Year award with [[University of Southern California|USC]]'s [[Marcus Allen]]. He earned ''Sports Illustrated'''s Player of the Week award after his performance against Colorado State, in which he tied a school record with 7 touchdown passes.\n\nIn his last game as a Cougar, McMahon passed for 342 yards and 3 touchdowns to lead BYU over [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington State]] in the 1981 Holiday Bowl. His career totals were 9,536 passing yards and 84 touchdown passes (not including bowl games). McMahon left college with 70 NCAA records{{r|rock20100904}} and tied for one other. He entered the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 1999.<ref>{{College Football HoF|id=2043|name=Jim \"Jimmy Mac\" McMahon  |accessdate=September 4, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, McMahon announced he would complete his coursework at BYU, which would qualify him for induction into the Brigham Young University Athletics Hall of Fame. On October 2, 2014, after completing his degree in communications, McMahon was inducted into the BYU Athletics Hall of Fame as part of the 2014 class.<ref>{{cite web|title=McMahon Inducted into BYU Hall of Fame|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865612288/Five-All-Americans-including-McMahon-inducted-into-BYU-Athletic-Hall-of-Fame.html}}</ref> BYU honored McMahon by retiring his No. 9 jersey during a halftime ceremony at the BYU vs. Utah State football game on Friday, October 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=McMahon's BYU jersey to be retired Oct. 3|url=http://byucougars.com/m-football/mcmahon's-byu-jersey-be-retired-oct-3}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Chicago Bears===\nThe [[1982 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] selected McMahon in the first round (fifth overall) of the [[1982 NFL Draft]]. New head coach [[Mike Ditka]] made McMahon his first first-round selection. McMahon, thrilled to be free from what he considered a restrictive culture at BYU, strolled into his first public function with the Bears holding a cold beer in his hand. Ditka was not impressed, nor was Bears owner and founder [[George Halas]]. McMahon was to find the atmosphere in Chicago almost as challenging as that at Brigham Young, and he would lock horns with Ditka routinely during his seven years with the Bears.\n\nMcMahon won the Bears' starting quarterback job as a rookie in [[1982 Chicago Bears season|1982]], and was named to several All-Rookie teams when he nearly led the team to the playoffs, despite the NFL only playing two games before a [[1982 NFL strike|players' strike]] that cancelled nearly half the season. McMahon quickly displayed a natural ability to read defenses and an athletic versatility that surprised many.\n\nMcMahon also made a case for being the best rollout passer at that time. He explained that coaching in his youth had taught him to square his shoulders to the direction he wanted to throw the football, and he was thus able to execute passes with tight spirals and a high degree of accuracy when running to either his left or his right. The Bears finished the strike-shortened season at 3\u20136, but due to an expanded playoff format and conference-wide seeding the Bears missed a playoff berth by only one victory. McMahon was named [[National Football Conference|NFC]] Offensive Rookie of the Year, losing the league-wide honor to [[Marcus Allen]].\n\nIn [[1983 Chicago Bears season|1983]], McMahon continued to improve as a passer and as a field general. He made a habit of changing the play both in the huddle and at the line of scrimmage, a practice which frustrated Ditka but usually led to success. His knowledge of the game and an instinctive, intuitive grasp of in-game situations were significant. He became a frequent scorer in goal line situations, after the dying Halas instructed Ditka to make the quarterback sneak a bigger part of the Bears' offense. He also began to catch touchdown passes on option plays, and was the emergency punter. Chicago finished the season at 8\u20138, missing the division title and a playoff berth by one victory again.\n\nIn [[1984 Chicago Bears season|1984]], the Bears broke through, reaching the conference title game before losing to the [[1984 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]]. McMahon started the season strongly, though nursing minor injuries like those that would plague him throughout his career. In a violent game against the [[1984 Los Angeles Raiders season|Los Angeles Raiders]] in Chicago, McMahon sustained a season-ending injury when he was brutally tackled by two Los Angeles defenders. He suffered bruised ribs and a lacerated kidney on the play, but limped to the huddle and breathlessly called the next play, despite difficulty breathing and increasing pain. The players could barely hear him in the huddle, and when McMahon attempted an audible at the line of scrimmage the Bears receivers were unable to hear his call. McMahon was on the verge of collapsing on the field, clutching his flank and rasping in his attempts to convey his situation. Offensive linemen helped McMahon stand and leave the field. McMahon went to the locker room, and reported urine that \"looked like grape juice.\"\n\n====1985====\n[[File:1986 Jeno's Pizza - 11 - Jim McMahon (Jim McMahon crop).jpg|thumb|150px|right|Jim McMahon dives into the end zone to score a touchdown during Super Bowl XX.]]\n[[File:1985 Chicago Bears Visit the White House.webm|thumb|right|300px|'1985 Chicago Bears Visit the White House' - video from White House]]\nIn [[1985 Chicago Bears season|1985]], the Bears won their first 12 games and finished at 15\u20131. McMahon became a media darling, not only for his outstanding play on the field, but also for his personality. He appeared in a [[hip hop music|rap]] record made by the team, \"The [[Super Bowl Shuffle]],\" in which he proclaimed ''\"I'm the punky QB known as McMahon.\"'' He ended the season with a strong performance in [[Super Bowl XX]], which the Bears won 46\u201310 over the [[1985 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]. In that game, McMahon became the first quarterback in the history of the Super Bowl to rush for two touchdowns.<ref>NFL 2001 Record and Fact Book, Edited by Randall Liu, p. 349, Workman Publishing, 2001, {{ISBN|0-7611-2480-2}}</ref> McMahon earned a spot in his only [[1986 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]].\n\nMcMahon was notorious for head-first [[baseball]]-style slides when running the football, despite being coached to slide feet-first to protect his body. In the playoffs McMahon heeded this coaching advice and was speared by a defender's helmet squarely in his buttocks, causing a painful deep bruise for which McMahon sought [[acupuncture]] treatment.<ref>In Life, First You Kick Ass: Reflections on the 1985 Bears and Wisdom from Da Coach, Mike Ditka with Rick Telander, Sports Publishing, 2005, {{ISBN|978-1-58261-977-4}}</ref> This led to a point of controversy before the [[Super Bowl]] in New Orleans, when McMahon \"[[Mooning|mooned]]\" journalists who were inquiring as to the status of the injury. \n\nIn an early-season Thursday night game at Minnesota, McMahon was slated to back up [[Steve Fuller (American football)|Steve Fuller]], as McMahon had missed practice time earlier in the week due to a neck injury that required an overnight hospital stay. Midway into the third quarter, the Vikings held a 17\u20139 lead. McMahon lobbied to get into the game until well into the third quarter. Once finally on the field, his first play was an opportunistic 70-yard touchdown pass to [[Willie Gault]]. After an interception by Wilber Marshall on the Vikings ensuing possession, McMahon's very next offensive play was a 25-yard touchdown pass to [[Dennis McKinnon]], making him 2\u20132 for 95 yards and two [[touchdown]]s. He followed up with another successful offensive drive, including a crucial third and short sneak to set up another 43-yard touchdown pass to McKinnon. The Bears led 30\u201317 and went on to win the game 33\u201324.\n\nMcMahon was fined $5,000 for violating the league's dress code by wearing an [[Adidas]] headband.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-11-15/sports/0911140277_1_chad-ochocinco-nfl-halas | work=Chicago Tribune | title=Chicago Bears' Jim McMahon was the Chad Ochocinco of his day | date=November 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n====1986\u20131988====\n{{Further|Charles Martin (American football)#1986 McMahon incident}}\nIn week 12 of the 1986 NFL regular season, McMahon was playing against the Green Bay Packers, while dealing with an existing rotator cuff injury to his right shoulder. After throwing a 3rd down interception and at least two seconds after his pass was thrown, Green Bay nose tackle [[Charles Martin (football player)|Charles Martin]] grabbed McMahon from behind and body-slammed him to the ground. McMahon hit the frozen artificial turf at Soldier Field shoulder first, exacerbating his existing rotator cuff injury. He briefly returned to the game, but it soon became apparent that he couldn't throw effectively, and he left the game in the third quarter, never to play again in 1986. Martin was immediately ejected from the game and later suspended for two additional games \u2014 the first multi-game suspension for an on-field incident in modern NFL history. Without McMahon, and despite finishing tied for the league's best record at 14\u20132, the Bears were unable to defend their Super Bowl championship and lost in the Divisional Playoff round to the [[1986 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]].\n\nMcMahon battled injuries for the rest of his career although at one point between the 1984 and [[1987 Chicago Bears season|1987]] seasons, he won 22 consecutive regular-season (25 including playoffs and the Super Bowl) starts, the longest \"regular season winning streak\" by an NFL quarterback at the time, now held by [[Peyton Manning]], who won 23 in 2008 to 2009 (but lost a wildcard playoff game to the Chargers during his \"winning streak\").\n\nIn 1987, he came right back from a head injury in a game against the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]. McMahon brought the Chicago Bears back in the first game following the [[1987 NFL strike|1987 NFL players strike]] to defeat the Buccaneers, 27\u201326. The Bears went on to an 11\u20134 record with many expecting McMahon to lead the Bears back to the Super Bowl. However, 1987 ended exactly the same way 1986 did with the Bears eliminated by the [[1987 Washington Redskins season|eventual Super Bowl champion Redskins]].\n\nMcMahon returned for the [[1988 Chicago Bears season|1988]] season with a much more serious attitude. His main offensive weapon in [[Walter Payton]] had retired and McMahon publicly expressed his desire to win a Super Bowl again. The Bears looked strong all season and went 12\u20134, again winning the NFC Central, and finishing with the NFC's top seed, ensuring they would host the NFC Championship Game at Soldier Field if they advanced that far. McMahon was unable to get the Bears back to the Super Bowl, as they were routed by the eventual Super Bowl champion [[1988 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] in the NFC Championship which saw McMahon benched in favor of [[Mike Tomczak]] in the fourth quarter.\n\nDuring the offseason, McMahon and Bears president [[Michael McCaskey]] had a major falling out with each other. He also fell out of favor with head coach [[Mike Ditka]], and after spending his first seven seasons in the league with Chicago, McMahon was traded to the [[1989 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]].\n\n{{As of|2017}}'s NFL off-season, Jim McMahon held at least 15 Bears franchise records, including:\n* Completions: playoffs (70)\n* Passing Yards: playoffs (967), playoff season (636 in 1985)\n* Passing TDs: playoffs (4), playoff season (3 in 1985; with [[Rex Grossman]]), playoff game (2 on 1986-01-05 NYG; with [[Steve Walsh (American football)|Steve Walsh]] and [[Jay Cutler (American football)|Jay Cutler]]), rookie season (9 in 1982; with [[Kyle Orton]])\n* Passer Rating: playoffs (77.1), playoff season (106.6 in 1985), rookie season (79.9 in 1982)\n* Sacked: playoffs (10), rookie game (7 on 1982-11-28 @MIN)\n* Yds/Pass Att: playoffs (7.61), playoff season (9.64 in 1985)\n* Pass Yds/Game: rookie season (187.6 in 1982)\n\n===San Diego Chargers===\nMcMahon started 12 games for the 6\u201310 [[San Diego Chargers|Chargers]] team in 1989. He went 4\u20138 in the games he started, though the team lost 4 of those games by a combined 11 points. He had only 4 games over 200 yards, but had 389 yards against the [[Houston Oilers]] in a Week 2 loss.\n\nHowever, McMahon again found himself in trouble when he fell out of favor with his coach, [[Dan Henning]], his teammates, and the team's front office staff. He was benched for the final four games in favor of [[Billy Joe Tolliver]] and finished the year with 2,132 yards, 10 touchdowns and 10 interceptions. He was released after the season.\n\n===Later career===\n[[File:Jim McMahon and Obama.jpg|thumb|upright|McMahon at the [[White House]] with [[Barack Obama|President Obama]] in 2011.]]\nMcMahon signed with the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], who were coached by former Bears assistant [[Buddy Ryan]], for the 1990 season. For the first time in his career he served as a full-time backup as [[Randall Cunningham]] was entrenched as the starter. After Cunningham tore his ACL in the opening game of the following season, new coach [[Rich Kotite]] named McMahon his starter. He led the Eagles to a 10\u20136 record, including a Week 17 win over the 14\u20131 [[Washington Redskins]], and earned the [[NFL Comeback Player of the Year]] award. He stayed with the Eagles for one additional season as the backup to Cunningham.\n\nMcMahon's last chance to be a full-time starter came with the [[Minnesota Vikings]] in [[1993 NFL season|1993]]. Supplanting [[Sean Salisbury]] as the team's starter, McMahon led the Vikings to eight wins in twelve starts and returned to the postseason as a starter for the first time since 1988. However, the Vikings lost to the [[New York Giants]].\n\nAfter the season, McMahon joined the [[Arizona Cardinals]], now coached by Ryan, for the 1994 season, where he made his final career start in Week 3 against the [[Cleveland Browns]]. He finished the season as the team's third quarterback behind [[Steve Beuerlein]] and [[Jay Schroeder]] and left the team at its conclusion. After failing to catch on with the Browns in the 1995 preseason, McMahon joined the [[Green Bay Packers]]. He retired following the [[1996 NFL season|1996]] season, which finished with a Green Bay Super Bowl victory over the New England Patriots in New Orleans, eleven years to the day of the Bears' Super Bowl victory over the Patriots in the same venue.\n\nMcMahon caused some controversy when he showed up to the Packers' reception at the [[White House]] wearing his Bears jersey, due to the rivalry between the two teams. McMahon later explained that he did so because he was unable to visit the White House when he led the Bears to victory in Super Bowl XX; two days after the Bears won the game, the crew of [[Space Shuttle]] mission [[STS-51-L]] were killed in the [[Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|explosion]] of their craft, Shuttle ''[[Space Shuttle Challenger|Challenger]]'', and the Bears' scheduled visit was cancelled. McMahon and his surviving teammates and coaches were eventually received in 2011 by President [[Barack Obama]], himself a Bears fan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobears.com/news/ChalkTalkStory.asp?STORY_ID=4853|title=The Official Website of the Chicago Bears|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Post-retirement==\n\n===Legal trouble===\nSince retiring from football in [[1997 NFL season|1997]], he has worked as a restaurant owner and motivational speaker. He was apprehended in Florida for [[drunk driving]] in 2003. Upon being pulled over, McMahon allegedly got out of his car and said to the police, \"I'm too drunk; you got me.\"<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=1658175 \"McMahon 'wasted' while driving\"], ESPN.com, Accessed December 10, 2006</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 2012 it was reported by the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', that McMahon was targeted by the [[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation]] (FDIC) for $104 million in bad loans made by the now closed, Chicago-based [[Broadway Bank (Illinois)|Broadway Bank]], of which he was a member of the board. The FDIC wanted to recover $104 million in loans made by the bank before it was shut down, according to the newspaper. In addition to McMahon, six other former Broadway Bank board members and two former bank executives had been targeted. It is said that McMahon had only approved one loan out of the 17 bad loans for a $28 million Miami beach condo project. The FDIC said the bank lost $19.5 million on the loan, according to the ''Sun-Times''. McMahon said in a statement to the ''Sun-Times'' that the FDIC's claims were without merit and he expected to be vindicated. \"I am proud to have served as an outside, independent director for a brief part of the bank's history,\" he wrote, according to the ''Sun-Times''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/blogs/chicago/feds-target-former-bears-qb-mcmahon-145949993.html/|title=Feds target former Bears QB McMahon|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Concussions===\nIn a November 6, 2010, interview, McMahon admitted to having memory problems due to injuries suffered on the football field. McMahon was quoted as saying, 'There are a lot of times when I walk into a room and forget why I walked in there.'<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/ct-spt-1107-around-town--20101105,0,7989581,print.column|work=Chicago Tribune|title=Chicagotribune.Com|first1=Fred|last1=Mitchell|first2=David|last2=Kaplan|date=November 6, 2010}}</ref> McMahon, along with six other retired professional football players, filed a class action lawsuit against the NFL in August 2011, citing the league's negligence and misconduct in its handling of concussion-related injuries; the suit followed lawsuits filed shortly before by 75 other NFL retirees making similar claims as well as asserting that the NFL knew about the dangers concussions posed to NFL athletes as far back as the 1920s and actively withheld the information from the affected and the general public until the summer of 2010. The August suit that McMahon joined seeks to expand the scope of the suit to potentially all NFL players who suffered game-related concussions or head injuries.<ref>{{cite web|last=Associated Press|title=Players accuse NFL of negligence|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/6874906/jim-mcmahon-other-players-sue-nfl-concussions|publisher=espn.com|accessdate=March 19, 2012|date=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared in a ''Sports Illustrated'' cover article in September 2012 detailing his struggles.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csnchicago.com/football-chicago-bears/bears-talk/Sports-Illustrated-features-McMahon-real?blockID=768219&feedID=10330 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130121184635/http://www.csnchicago.com/football-chicago-bears/bears-talk/Sports-Illustrated-features-McMahon-real?blockID=768219&feedID=10330 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 21, 2013 |title=Sports Illustrated features McMahon, reality of concussions |last=Falcone |first=Nina |date=September 5, 2012 |work=CSNChicago.com |accessdate=September 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 2012, it was reported that at age 53 McMahon had been diagnosed as being in the early stages of [[dementia]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hendrix|first=Maggie|title=Super Bowl-winning quarterback Jim McMahon says he wishes he had played baseball|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/super-bowl-winning-quarterback-jim-mcmahon-says-wishes-192055029--nfl.html|publisher=Yahoo!}}</ref>\n\nThe Sports Illustrated article caught the attention of New York Chiropractor Scott Rosa who reached out to McMahon with an offer of treatment. Rosa believed that McMahon's neck was out of alignment caused by his years of playing football. Rosa performed an adjustment on his neck that repaired a blockage and allowed spinal fluid to drain normally. The procedure had positive results. \u201cThe first time he did it, my head was so full of stuff it literally felt like the toilet flushing,\u201d he said. \u201cI could actually feel the stuff draining out of my head.\u201d McMahon had daily adjustments for a week and now only returns for an adjustment every 3 months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pilotonline.com/sports/columnist/harry-minium/article_0cb3ba9f-4b24-551d-98c5-30a86b8a83d8.html|title=Ex-NFL star Jim McMahon was nearly driven to suicide by headaches from too many head blows|last=Minium|first=Harry|website=Virginian-Pilot|language=en|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> This treatment has led to improvement in his short term memory and the elimination of his headaches.<ref name=\"sfchronicle.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/sports/ostler/article/Ex-NFL-star-Jim-McMahon-spreading-gospel-of-golf-11290279.php|title=Ex-NFL star Jim McMahon spreading gospel of golf, new treatment - SFChronicle.com|date=2017-07-15|website=www.sfchronicle.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref>\n\n===Medical cannabis===\nMcMahon uses [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] to treat the chronic pain and arthritis that he suffers from as a result of his football career.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Magers|first1=Ron|title=Jim Mcmahon Says Medical Marijuana Helped Him Kick Pain Pill Habit|url=http://abc7chicago.com/news/jim-mcmahon-says-marijuana-helped-him-kick-pain-pills/1177764/|accessdate=June 9, 2016|work=ABC7 Eyewitness News|date=January 28, 2016}}</ref>  He calls cannabis a \"godsend\" that allowed him to completely eliminate his painkiller habit which he says included 100 [[Percocet]] pills a month.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCoppin|first1=Robert|title=Ex-Bear Jim McMahon: Medical marijuana got me off narcotic pain pills|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-chicago-bears-jim-mcmahon-medical-marijuana-met-20160128-story.html|accessdate=June 9, 2016|work=Chicago Tribune|date=January 29, 2016}}</ref>  McMahon has been active in speaking about his experience using cannabis, serving as spokesperson for the Cannabis Sports Policy Project<ref>{{cite press release |title=North American Cannabis Holdings and Former Chicago Bears QB Jim McMahon Announce The Cannabis Sports Policy Project |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/north-american-cannabis-holdings-and-former-chicago-bears-qb-jim-mcmahon-announce-the-cannabis-sports-policy-project-576210791.html |agency=PR Newswire |date=April 19, 2016 |access-date=June 9, 2016}}</ref> and a member of the Gridiron Cannabis Coalition along with several other former NFL players.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blackburn|first1=Peter|title=Ex-NFL stars use Netflix to share pro-cannabis PSA calling out Roger Goodell|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/watch-ex-nfl-stars-use-netflix-to-share-pro-cannabis-psa-calling-out-roger-goodell/|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=CBS Sports|date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>  McMahon appeared in a TV ad supporting cannabis legalization in the state of Arizona.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peake|first1=Gage|title=Ex-Bears QB Jim McMahon Stumps for Arizona Legalization|url=https://www.leafly.com/news/politics/ex-bears-qb-jim-mcmahon-stumps-arizona-legalization|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=Leafly|date=October 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, McMahon was among the signatories of an [[open letter]] addressed to the NFL, urging a change in the league's policy towards cannabis.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jhabvala|first1=Nicki|title=Players, Doctors for Cannabis Regulation pen letter to NFL urging policy reform|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2016/11/11/players-doctors-for-cannabis-regulation-pen-letter-nfl/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|work=The Denver Post|date=November 11, 2016}}</ref>  The letter was penned by [[Doctors for Cannabis Regulation]] and signed by several other NFL players.<ref>{{cite |title=An Open Letter to the National Football League |url=https://dfcr.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/NFL-open-letter.pdf |publisher=Doctors for Cannabis Regulation |date=November 11, 2016}}</ref>  McMahon is also a member of the Doctors for Cannabis Regulation NFL steering committee.<ref>{{cite web |title=NFL Campaign |url=https://dfcr.org/nfl-campaign/ |website=Doctors for Cannabis Regulation |accessdate=October 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other activities===\n[[Image:Jim McMahon in Iraq with the 15th MEU.jpg|thumb|right|225px|McMahon being greeted by the Commanding Officer of the [[15th MEU]] during his [[USO]] tour in [[Iraq]] in December 2006.]]\nIn December 2006 McMahon went to [[Iraq]] with the [[United Service Organizations|USO]] to visit American forces in the field.<ref>\n{{cite web|authorlink=United States Marine Corps|title=Celebrities drop in to pay the 15th MEU a holiday visit|publisher=15th Marine Expeditionary Unit|url=http://www.usmc.mil/15thmeu/PAGES/PHOTO_PAGES/070111_celeb_visit.htm}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Super Bowl XLIV]], McMahon joined other members of the 1985 Chicago Bears in resurrecting the [[Super Bowl Shuffle]] in a [[Boost Mobile]] commercial.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jon Greenberg |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/nfl/columns/story?columnist=greenberg_jon&id=4827883 |title=Chicago Bears' \"Super Bowl Shuffle\" an enduring, endearing sports moment \u2013 ESPN Chicago |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=January 15, 2010 |accessdate=July 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, McMahon became a part owner of the [[Indoor Football League]]'s [[Chicago Slaughter]].\n\nIn November 2012, McMahon appeared on an episode of the sitcom ''[[The League]]'' called \"The Tailgate.\"\n\n==Playing style==\nThroughout his career, McMahon was known for both on- and off-field antics. Most famously, his wearing of a [[headband]] while on the sidelines once led to him being fined by then NFL commissioner, [[Pete Rozelle]], as it had an unauthorized corporate logo (Adidas) on it. The next week his headband simply said \"Rozelle\". (The commissioner later admitted in a letter to McMahon that the headband with Rozelle's name was \"funny as hell\", but declined to rescind the $5,000 fine.) Reportedly before Super Bowl XX hundreds of fans mailed McMahon headbands in hopes he would wear them during the game; Rozelle warned the quarterback not to wear anything \"unacceptable\". In response, McMahon decided to help bring attention to [[Diabetes mellitus type 1|Juvenile Diabetes]] by wearing a headband simply stating \"JDF Cure\", before switching to one stating \"[[National League of Families POW/MIA Flag|POW-MIA]]\", and finally one with the word \"Pluto\", the nickname of his close friend and favorite collegiate receiving target, former BYU wide receiver Danny Plater, who was afflicted with a brain tumor.<ref>Benson, Lee. And They Came to Pass. Salt Lake City: Deseret Book, 1988. Print.\n</ref>\n\nHe also is known for his trademark sunglasses, which he wears for medical reasons. At age six, while trying to untie a knot in a toy gun holster with a fork, he accidentally severed the cornea in his right eye when the fork slipped. While his [[visual perception|vision]] was saved, the accident left that eye extremely sensitive to [[light]].<ref>''[[America's Game: The Super Bowl Champions]]'', \"#2. 1985 Chicago Bears.\" Premiered on [[CBS]], February 3, 2007</ref> On the field he was among the first to wear a helmet fitted with a tinted plastic visor covering the eyes, leading to nicknames like \"Darth Vader\" and \"Black Sunshine.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiedeman |first1=Reeves |title=What's in a Nickname? |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/sporting-scene/whats-in-a-nickname |website=The New Yorker |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=October 7, 2011}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nMcMahon occasionally would play wearing gloves, and urged former NFL quarterback [[David Carr (American football)|David Carr]] to also wear gloves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carolinagrowl.com/Read.aspx?Story=235|title=HugeDomains.com - CarolinaGrowl.com is for sale (Carolina Growl)|website=www.carolinagrowl.com}}</ref>\n\n==Career stats==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! G\n! Passing<br />Att.-Comp.\n! Yards\n! Pct.\n! TD\n! Int.\n! Sacks-Lost\n! Pass<br />Rating\n|-\n| [[1982 Chicago Bears season|1982]]\n| rowspan=\"7\"|[[Chicago Bears|Chicago]]\n| 8\n| 210\u2013120\n| 1,501\n| .571\n| 9\n| 7\n| 27\u2013196\n| 79.9\n|-\n| [[1983 Chicago Bears season|1983]]\n| 14\n| 295\u2013175\n| 2,184\n| .593\n| 12\n| 13\n| 42\u2013266\n| 77.6\n|-\n| [[1984 Chicago Bears season|1984]]\n| 9\n| 143\u201385\n| 1,146\n| .594\n| 8\n| 2\n| 10\u201348\n| 97.8\n|-\n| [[1985 Chicago Bears season|1985]]\n| 13\n| 313\u2013178\n| 2,392\n| .569\n| 15\n| 11\n| 26\u2013125\n| 82.6\n|-\n| [[1986 Chicago Bears season|1986]]\n| 6\n| 150\u201377\n| 995\n| .513\n| 5\n| 8\n| 6\u201340\n| 61.4\n|-\n| [[1987 Chicago Bears season|1987]]\n| 7\n| 210\u2013125\n| 1,639\n| .595\n| 12\n| 8\n| 22\u2013136\n| 87.4\n|-\n| [[1988 Chicago Bears season|1988]]\n| 9\n| 192\u2013114\n| 1,346\n| .594\n| 6\n| 7\n| 13\u201379\n| 76.0\n|-\n| [[1989 San Diego Chargers season|1989]]\n| [[San Diego Chargers|San Diego]]\n| 12\n| 318\u2013176\n| 2,132\n| .553\n| 10\n| 10\n| 28\u2013167\n| 73.5\n|-\n| [[1990 Philadelphia Eagles season|1990]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[Philadelphia Eagles|Philadelphia]]\n| 5\n| 9\u20136\n| 63\n| .667\n| 0\n| 0\n| 1\u20137\n| 86.8\n|-\n| [[1991 Philadelphia Eagles season|1991]]\n| 12\n| 311\u2013187\n| 2,239\n| .601\n| 12\n| 11\n| 21\u2013128\n| 80.3\n|-\n| [[1992 Philadelphia Eagles season|1992]]\n| 4\n| 43\u201322\n| 279\n| .512\n| 1\n| 2\n| 4\u201325\n| 60.1\n|-\n| [[1993 Minnesota Vikings season|1993]]\n| [[Minnesota Vikings|Minnesota]]\n| 12\n| 331\u2013200\n| 1,968\n| .604\n| 9\n| 8\n| 23\u2013104\n| 76.2\n|-\n| [[1994 Arizona Cardinals season|1994]]\n| [[Arizona Cardinals|Arizona]]\n| 3\n| 43\u201323\n| 219\n| .535\n| 1\n| 3\n| 3\u201323\n| 46.6\n|-\n| [[1995 Green Bay Packers season|1995]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Green Bay Packers|Green Bay]]\n| 1\n| 1\u20131\n| 6\n| 1.00\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\u20130\n| 91.7\n|-\n| [[1996 Green Bay Packers season|1996]]\n| 5\n| 4\u20133\n| 39\n| .750\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\u20130\n| 105.2\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Totals\n| 120\n| 2,573\u20131,492\n| 18,148\n| .580\n| 100\n| 90\n| 226\u20131,344\n| 78.2\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Playoff Totals\n| 8\n| 155\u201382\n| 1,112\n| .643\n| 5\n| 4\n| n/a-n/a\n| 76.1\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nMcMahon met Nancy Daines at BYU, and the couple married in 1982 after four years of dating.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Benson|first1=Lee|title=And They Came To Pass|date=1988}}</ref> They have four children together and divorced in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rodkin|first1=Denis|title=Jim McMahon Sells His Northbrook Home|url=http://www.chicagomag.com/Radar/Deal-Estate/October-2009/Jim-McMahon-Sells-His-Northbrook-Home/|publisher=Chicago Magazine}}</ref> He was in a romantic relationship with Laurie Navon who was cited in the Sports Illustrated article where his health was discussed.<ref name=\":0\" /> The specifics of his relationship with Navon are not known, but more recent media reports currently have him in a relationship with Mayra Montoya.<ref name=\"sfchronicle.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zimbio.com/photos/Jim+McMahon/2018+Derek+Jeter+Celebrity+Invitational+Gala/t12ni6um0nd|title=Jim McMahon Photos Photos: 2018 Derek Jeter Celebrity Invitational Gala|website=Zimbio|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of NCAA Division I FBS quarterbacks with at least 80 career passing touchdowns]]\n* [[List of NCAA major college football yearly passing leaders]]\n* [[List of NCAA major college football yearly total offense leaders]]\n*[[List of NFL players with chronic traumatic encephalopathy#Living former players diagnosed with or reporting symptoms of CTE|Living former players diagnosed with or reporting symptoms of chronic traumatic encephalopathy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jim McMahon}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.swangwear.com}}\n* {{cfbhof|id=2043|name=Jim McMahon}}\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=MCM166115 |espn=6406 |cbs= |yahoo= |si= |pfr=M/McMaJi00 |rotoworld=}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| list1 = \n{{Super Bowl XX}}\n{{Super Bowl XXXI}}\n{{Davey O'Brien Award}}\n{{1981 NCAA Division I-A College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{1982 NFL Draft}}\n{{BearsFirstPick}}\n{{Bears1982DraftPicks}}\n{{Super Bowl Champion quarterbacks}}\n{{NFL Comeback Players of the Year}}\n{{NCAA major college football passing yardage leaders}}\n{{BYU Cougars quarterback navbox}}\n{{Chicago Bears starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{San Diego Chargers starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Philadelphia Eagles starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Minnesota Vikings starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Arizona Cardinals starting quarterback navbox}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McMahon, Jim}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Roy, Utah]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Utah]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:BYU Cougars football players]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears players]]\n[[Category:San Diego Chargers players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Concussion activists]]\n[[Category:American cannabis activists]]\n[[Category:Legends Football League coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the British politician|Jim McMahon (politician)}}\n{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|image=Jim McMahon (cropped).jpg\n|caption=McMahon at [[Hanscom Air Force Base]]<br>in [[Massachusetts]] in 1988\n|image_size=275\n|position=[[Quarterback]]\n|number=9\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1959|8|21}}\n|birth_place=[[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]], [[New Jersey]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place= \n|high_school = [[Roy High School (Utah)|Roy (UT)]]\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 1\n|weight_lbs = 195\n|draftyear=1982\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=5\n|college=[[BYU Cougars football|BYU]]\n|pastteams=\n* [[Chicago Bears]] ([[1982 NFL season|1982]]\u2013[[1988 NFL season|1988]])\n* [[San Diego Chargers]] ([[1989 NFL season|1989]])\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ([[1990 NFL season|1990]]\u2013[[1992 NFL season|1992]])\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ([[1993 NFL season|1993]])\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] ([[1994 NFL season|1994]])\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ([[1995 NFL season|1995]])*\n* [[Green Bay Packers]] ([[1995 NFL season|1995]]\u2013[[1996 NFL season|1996]])\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|statlabel1= Games Played\n|statvalue1= 119\n|statlabel2= Games Started\n|statvalue2= 97\n|statlabel3=[[Touchdown|TD]]s\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n|statvalue3=100\u201390\n|statlabel4=Yards\n|statvalue4=18,148\n|statlabel5=[[Passer rating|QB Rating]]\n|statvalue5=78.2\n|nfl=MCM166115\n|highlights=\n'''NCAA'''\n* 2\u00d7 Holiday Bowl MVP\n* 2\u00d7 [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[1980 College Football All-America Team|1980]], [[1981 College Football All-America Team|1981]])\n* 1981 [[Davey O'Brien Award]] winner\n* 1981 [[Sammy Baugh Trophy]] winner\n* [[BYU Cougars football|BYU Cougars #9 retired]]\n'''NFL'''\n* [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1986 Pro Bowl|1985]])\n* [[United Press International|UPI]] 2nd-Team All-NFC (1985)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XX|XX]], [[Super Bowl XXXI|XXXI]])\n* [[Brian Piccolo Award]] (1982)\n* [[UPI NFL-NFC Rookie of the Year|''UPI'' NFC Rookie of the Year]] (1982)\n* [[National Football League Comeback Player of the Year Award#PFW/PFWA Comeback Player of the Year award (1972\u2013present)|''PFW'' NFL Comeback Player of the Year]] (1991)\n|CollegeHOF=2043\n|name=Jim McMahon\n|}}\n'''James Robert McMahon Jr.''' (born August 21, 1959) is an American former [[American football|football]] player. He played [[college football]] at [[Brigham Young University]], where he was a two-time All-American ([[1980 College Football All-America Team|1980]], [[1981 College Football All-America Team|1981]]) and later in the professional ranks with the [[Chicago Bears]], [[San Diego Chargers]], [[Philadelphia Eagles]], [[Minnesota Vikings]], [[Arizona Cardinals]], [[Cleveland Browns]], and [[Green Bay Packers]].\n\nHe won two Super Bowl titles, the first with the Bears in [[Super Bowl XX]] where he was the starting quarterback, and the second with their rivals, the Green Bay Packers, in [[Super Bowl XXXI]] where he was a backup to [[Brett Favre]]. Both Super Bowls were against the [[New England Patriots]]. McMahon was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 1998.\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]], [[New Jersey]], McMahon moved with his family to [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]] when he was three.<ref name=\"ESPN Classic\" /> He played high school football his freshman and sophomore years at [[Andrew Hill High School]] in San Jose, then moved with his family in the summer of 1975 to [[Roy, Utah]]. He played his junior and senior years at [[Roy High School (Utah)|Roy High School]] and graduated in 1977.<ref name=\"ESPN Classic\">{{cite web|last=Carter|first=Bob|title=McMahon was a rebel without pause|url=http://espn.go.com/classic/biography/s/McMahon_Jim.html|publisher=ESPN Classic|accessdate=July 1, 2011|year=2007}}</ref><ref name=rbanaa>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=r9BSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KX8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5962%2C4783960 |work=Deseret News |location=(Salt Lake City, Utah) |last=Blodgett |first=Gary R. |title=Roy back an All-American |date=December 15, 1976 |page=6D}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nMcMahon mainly served as [[BYU]]'s punter during his [[1977 BYU Cougars football team|freshman season]]. Also he played baseball (1977), but he played enough at quarterback to throw his first-ever collegiate touchdown pass against [[UTEP Miners football|UTEP]]. He continued as the Cougars' punter as the [[1978 BYU Cougars football team|1978]] season began, but when [[Marc Wilson (American football)|Marc Wilson]] was injured in the third game of the season (against [[Colorado State Rams football|Colorado State]]), McMahon became the starting quarterback. McMahon led BYU to victory against CSU, accounting for 112 passing yards, 80 rushing yards, and two touchdowns. He was named Chevrolet Player of the Game and [[Western Athletic Conference|WAC]] Player of the Week for his performance. McMahon and Wilson shared quarterback duties for the rest of the season; McMahon played well enough to earn All-WAC honors and [[Associated Press]] Honorable Mention [[All-America]]. The best game of his sophomore year was against [[Wyoming Cowboys football|Wyoming]]: he passed for 317 yards and rushed for 49 more yards, earning another WAC Player of the Week award.\n\nMcMahon had suffered a knee injury towards the end of the 1978 season and BYU coaches chose to [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] him in [[1979 BYU Cougars football team|1979]]. McMahon watched from the sidelines as Wilson set nine [[NCAA]] records, tied two others, and became the first BYU player to earn consensus first team [[1979 College Football All-America Team|All-American]] honors; he finished third in [[Heisman Trophy]] [[1979 NCAA Division I-A football season#Heisman Trophy|balloting]].\n\nWith Wilson graduated and in the [[1980 NFL season|NFL]] with the [[1980 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], McMahon beat out Royce Bybee to claim the starting quarterback position in [[1980 BYU Cougars football team|1980]]. BYU lost the opener 25\u201321 against [[New Mexico Lobos football|New Mexico]], but then won eleven straight to claim the WAC championship. McMahon set 32 NCAA records, including single-season records for yards of total offense (4,627), passing yards (4,571), touchdown passes (47), and passing efficiency (176.9). His best game was against [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]]; he completed 21 of 33 passes for 485 yards and six touchdowns, and added two rushing touchdowns. That performance earned him ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'''s National Player of the Week award. McMahon's season statistics might have been even better, but he spent significant time on the sidelines because the Cougars won many games by wide margins. Although he started all 12 regular season games, he only finished three of them.\n\nBYU led the nation in passing offense, total offense, and scoring offense during the regular season. McMahon earned numerous awards for his individual accomplishments, being named WAC Player of the Year, unanimous First Team All-WAC, Utah Sportsman of the Year, and [[Deseret News]] Athlete of the Year. He was named to four All-America teams and finished fifth in Heisman Trophy voting.\n\nIn the [[1980 Holiday Bowl|Holiday Bowl]], the Cougars faced an [[1980 SMU Mustangs football team|SMU]] team led by star running backs [[Craig James (running back)|Craig James]] and [[Eric Dickerson]], and the Mustangs built a 45\u201325 lead over BYU with just four minutes left in the game. As Cougar fans headed for the exits, McMahon screamed that the game was not over yet. He guided BYU's offense to three quick touchdowns, including a 41-yard [[Hail Mary pass]] to Clay Brown to win the game<ref name=\"rock20100904\">{{cite news|last=Rock|first=Brad|title= Jim McMahon forever BYU's favorite rebel|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/print/700062850/Jim-McMahon-forever-BYUs-favorite-rebel.html|accessdate=September 4, 2010|newspaper=Deseret News|date=September 4, 2010}}</ref> as time expired. It is regarded as one of the greatest comebacks in college football history;<ref name=\"30for30\">\"SMU fell to BYU as quarterback Jim McMahon engineered what many dubbed 'the greatest comeback in college football bowl history'.\" Duffy, Patrick (narrator). \"Pony Excess\", ''[[30 for 30]]''. ESPN, November 11, 2010.</ref> BYU fans refer to it as the \"Miracle Bowl\".\n\nIn McMahon's senior season in [[1981 BYU Cougars football team|1981]], despite missing two games due to injuries, he passed for 3,555 yards and 30 touchdowns in the regular season, again leading BYU to a WAC championship. For his efforts, he was named WAC Player of the Year and unanimous First Team All-WAC. On a national level, he was named [[1981 College Football All-America Team|First-team All-American]] by five different organizations and finished third in Heisman Trophy balloting. He received the [[Davey O'Brien]] Trophy and the [[Sammy Baugh]] Award, and he shared the Pigskin Club NCAA Offensive Player of the Year award with [[University of Southern California|USC]]'s [[Marcus Allen]]. He earned ''Sports Illustrated'''s Player of the Week award after his performance against Colorado State, in which he tied a school record with 7 touchdown passes.\n\nIn his last game as a Cougar, McMahon passed for 342 yards and 3 touchdowns to lead BYU over [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington State]] in the 1981 Holiday Bowl. His career totals were 9,536 passing yards and 84 touchdown passes (not including bowl games). McMahon left college with 70 NCAA records{{r|rock20100904}} and tied for one other. He entered the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 1999.<ref>{{College Football HoF|id=2043|name=Jim \"Jimmy Mac\" McMahon  |accessdate=September 4, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, McMahon announced he would complete his coursework at BYU, which would qualify him for induction into the Brigham Young University Athletics Hall of Fame. On October 2, 2014, after completing his degree in communications, McMahon was inducted into the BYU Athletics Hall of Fame as part of the 2014 class.<ref>{{cite web|title=McMahon Inducted into BYU Hall of Fame|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865612288/Five-All-Americans-including-McMahon-inducted-into-BYU-Athletic-Hall-of-Fame.html}}</ref> BYU honored McMahon by retiring his No. 9 jersey during a halftime ceremony at the BYU vs. Utah State football game on Friday, October 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=McMahon's BYU jersey to be retired Oct. 3|url=http://byucougars.com/m-football/mcmahon's-byu-jersey-be-retired-oct-3}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Chicago Bears===\nThe [[1982 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] selected McMahon in the first round (fifth overall) of the [[1982 NFL Draft]]. New head coach [[Mike Ditka]] made McMahon his first first-round selection. McMahon, thrilled to be free from what he considered a restrictive culture at BYU, strolled into his first public function with the Bears holding a cold beer in his hand. Ditka was not impressed, nor was Bears owner and founder [[George Halas]]. McMahon was to find the atmosphere in Chicago almost as challenging as that at Brigham Young, and he would lock horns with Ditka routinely during his seven years with the Bears.\n\nMcMahon won the Bears' starting quarterback job as a rookie in [[1982 Chicago Bears season|1982]], and was named to several All-Rookie teams when he nearly led the team to the playoffs, despite the NFL only playing two games before a [[1982 NFL strike|players' strike]] that cancelled nearly half the season. McMahon quickly displayed a natural ability to read defenses and an athletic versatility that surprised many.\n\nMcMahon also made a case for being the best rollout passer at that time. He explained that coaching in his youth had taught him to square his shoulders to the direction he wanted to throw the football, and he was thus able to execute passes with tight spirals and a high degree of accuracy when running to either his left or his right. The Bears finished the strike-shortened season at 3\u20136, but due to an expanded playoff format and conference-wide seeding the Bears missed a playoff berth by only one victory. McMahon was named [[National Football Conference|NFC]] Offensive Rookie of the Year, losing the league-wide honor to [[Marcus Allen]].\n\nIn [[1983 Chicago Bears season|1983]], McMahon continued to improve as a passer and as a field general. He made a habit of changing the play both in the huddle and at the line of scrimmage, a practice which frustrated Ditka but usually led to success. His knowledge of the game and an instinctive, intuitive grasp of in-game situations were significant. He became a frequent scorer in goal line situations, after the dying Halas instructed Ditka to make the quarterback sneak a bigger part of the Bears' offense. He also began to catch touchdown passes on option plays, and was the emergency punter. Chicago finished the season at 8\u20138, missing the division title and a playoff berth by one victory again.\n\nIn [[1984 Chicago Bears season|1984]], the Bears broke through, reaching the conference title game before losing to the [[1984 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]]. McMahon started the season strongly, though nursing minor injuries like those that would plague him throughout his career. In a violent game against the [[1984 Los Angeles Raiders season|Los Angeles Raiders]] in Chicago, McMahon sustained a season-ending injury when he was brutally tackled by two Los Angeles defenders. He suffered bruised ribs and a lacerated kidney on the play, but limped to the huddle and breathlessly called the next play, despite difficulty breathing and increasing pain. The players could barely hear him in the huddle, and when McMahon attempted an audible at the line of scrimmage the Bears receivers were unable to hear his call. McMahon was on the verge of collapsing on the field, clutching his flank and rasping in his attempts to convey his situation. Offensive linemen helped McMahon stand and leave the field. McMahon went to the locker room, and reported urine that \"looked like grape juice.\"\n\n====1985====\n[[File:1986 Jeno's Pizza - 11 - Jim McMahon (Jim McMahon crop).jpg|thumb|150px|right|Jim McMahon dives into the end zone to score a touchdown during Super Bowl XX.]]\n[[File:1985 Chicago Bears Visit the White House.webm|thumb|right|300px|'1985 Chicago Bears Visit the White House' - video from White House]]\nIn [[1985 Chicago Bears season|1985]], the Bears won their first 12 games and finished at 15\u20131. McMahon became a media darling, not only for his outstanding play on the field, but also for his personality. He appeared in a [[hip hop music|rap]] record made by the team, \"The [[Super Bowl Shuffle]],\" in which he proclaimed ''\"I'm the punky QB known as McMahon.\"'' He ended the season with a strong performance in [[Super Bowl XX]], which the Bears won 46\u201310 over the [[1985 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]. In that game, McMahon became the first quarterback in the history of the Super Bowl to rush for two touchdowns.<ref>NFL 2001 Record and Fact Book, Edited by Randall Liu, p. 349, Workman Publishing, 2001, {{ISBN|0-7611-2480-2}}</ref> McMahon earned a spot in his only [[1986 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]].\n\nMcMahon was notorious for head-first [[baseball]]-style slides when running the football, despite being coached to slide feet-first to protect his body. In the playoffs McMahon heeded this coaching advice and was speared by a defender's helmet squarely in his buttocks, causing a painful deep bruise for which McMahon sought [[acupuncture]] treatment.<ref>In Life, First You Kick Ass: Reflections on the 1985 Bears and Wisdom from Da Coach, Mike Ditka with Rick Telander, Sports Publishing, 2005, {{ISBN|978-1-58261-977-4}}</ref> This led to a point of controversy before the [[Super Bowl]] in New Orleans, when McMahon \"[[Mooning|mooned]]\" journalists who were inquiring as to the status of the injury. \n\nIn an early-season Thursday night game at Minnesota, McMahon was slated to back up [[Steve Fuller (American football)|Steve Fuller]], as McMahon had missed practice time earlier in the week due to a neck injury that required an overnight hospital stay. Midway into the third quarter, the Vikings held a 17\u20139 lead. McMahon lobbied to get into the game until well into the third quarter. Once finally on the field, his first play was an opportunistic 70-yard touchdown pass to [[Willie Gault]]. After an interception by Wilber Marshall on the Vikings ensuing possession, McMahon's very next offensive play was a 25-yard touchdown pass to [[Dennis McKinnon]], making him 2\u20132 for 95 yards and two [[touchdown]]s. He followed up with another successful offensive drive, including a crucial third and short sneak to set up another 43-yard touchdown pass to McKinnon. The Bears led 30\u201317 and went on to win the game 33\u201324.\n\nMcMahon was fined $5,000 for violating the league's dress code by wearing an [[Adidas]] headband.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-11-15/sports/0911140277_1_chad-ochocinco-nfl-halas | work=Chicago Tribune | title=Chicago Bears' Jim McMahon was the Chad Ochocinco of his day | date=November 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n====1986\u20131988====\n{{Further|Charles Martin (American football)#1986 McMahon incident}}\nIn week 12 of the 1986 NFL regular season, McMahon was playing against the Green Bay Packers, while dealing with an existing rotator cuff injury to his right shoulder. After throwing a 3rd down interception and at least two seconds after his pass was thrown, Green Bay nose tackle [[Charles Martin (football player)|Charles Martin]] grabbed McMahon from behind and body-slammed him to the ground. McMahon hit the frozen artificial turf at Soldier Field shoulder first, exacerbating his existing rotator cuff injury. He briefly returned to the game, but it soon became apparent that he couldn't throw effectively, and he left the game in the third quarter, never to play again in 1986. Martin was immediately ejected from the game and later suspended for two additional games \u2014 the first multi-game suspension for an on-field incident in modern NFL history. Without McMahon, and despite finishing tied for the league's best record at 14\u20132, the Bears were unable to defend their Super Bowl championship and lost in the Divisional Playoff round to the [[1986 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]].\n\nMcMahon battled injuries for the rest of his career although at one point between the 1984 and [[1987 Chicago Bears season|1987]] seasons, he won 22 consecutive regular-season (25 including playoffs and the Super Bowl) starts, the longest \"regular season winning streak\" by an NFL quarterback at the time, now held by [[Peyton Manning]], who won 23 in 2008 to 2009 (but lost a wildcard playoff game to the Chargers during his \"winning streak\").\n\nIn 1987, he came right back from a head injury in a game against the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]. McMahon brought the Chicago Bears back in the first game following the [[1987 NFL strike|1987 NFL players strike]] to defeat the Buccaneers, 27\u201326. The Bears went on to an 11\u20134 record with many expecting McMahon to lead the Bears back to the Super Bowl. However, 1987 ended exactly the same way 1986 did with the Bears eliminated by the [[1987 Washington Redskins season|eventual Super Bowl champion Redskins]].\n\nMcMahon returned for the [[1988 Chicago Bears season|1988]] season with a much more serious attitude. His main offensive weapon in [[Walter Payton]] had retired and McMahon publicly expressed his desire to win a Super Bowl again. The Bears looked strong all season and went 12\u20134, again winning the NFC Central, and finishing with the NFC's top seed, ensuring they would host the NFC Championship Game at Soldier Field if they advanced that far. McMahon was unable to get the Bears back to the Super Bowl, as they were routed by the eventual Super Bowl champion [[1988 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] in the NFC Championship which saw McMahon benched in favor of [[Mike Tomczak]] in the fourth quarter.\n\nDuring the offseason, McMahon and Bears president [[Michael McCaskey]] had a major falling out with each other. He also fell out of favor with head coach [[Mike Ditka]], and after spending his first seven seasons in the league with Chicago, McMahon was traded to the [[1989 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]].\n\n{{As of|2017}}'s NFL off-season, Jim McMahon held at least 15 Bears franchise records, including:\n* Completions: playoffs (70)\n* Passing Yards: playoffs (967), playoff season (636 in 1985)\n* Passing TDs: playoffs (4), playoff season (3 in 1985; with [[Rex Grossman]]), playoff game (2 on 1986-01-05 NYG; with [[Steve Walsh (American football)|Steve Walsh]] and [[Jay Cutler (American football)|Jay Cutler]]), rookie season (9 in 1982; with [[Kyle Orton]])\n* Passer Rating: playoffs (77.1), playoff season (106.6 in 1985), rookie season (79.9 in 1982)\n* Sacked: playoffs (10), rookie game (7 on 1982-11-28 @MIN)\n* Yds/Pass Att: playoffs (7.61), playoff season (9.64 in 1985)\n* Pass Yds/Game: rookie season (187.6 in 1982)\n\n===San Diego Chargers===\nMcMahon started 12 games for the 6\u201310 [[San Diego Chargers|Chargers]] team in 1989. He went 4\u20138 in the games he started, though the team lost 4 of those games by a combined 11 points. He had only 4 games over 200 yards, but had 389 yards against the [[Houston Oilers]] in a Week 2 loss.\n\nHowever, McMahon again found himself in trouble when he fell out of favor with his coach, [[Dan Henning]], his teammates, and the team's front office staff. He was benched for the final four games in favor of [[Billy Joe Tolliver]] and finished the year with 2,132 yards, 10 touchdowns and 10 interceptions. He was released after the season.\n\n===Later career===\n[[File:Jim McMahon and Obama.jpg|thumb|upright|McMahon at the [[White House]] with [[Barack Obama|President Obama]] in 2011.]]\nMcMahon signed with the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], who were coached by former Bears assistant [[Buddy Ryan]], for the 1990 season. For the first time in his career he served as a full-time backup as [[Randall Cunningham]] was entrenched as the starter. After Cunningham tore his ACL in the opening game of the following season, new coach [[Rich Kotite]] named McMahon his starter. He led the Eagles to a 10\u20136 record, including a Week 17 win over the 14\u20131 [[Washington Redskins]], and earned the [[NFL Comeback Player of the Year]] award. He stayed with the Eagles for one additional season as the backup to Cunningham.\n\nMcMahon's last chance to be a full-time starter came with the [[Minnesota Vikings]] in [[1993 NFL season|1993]]. Supplanting [[Sean Salisbury]] as the team's starter, McMahon led the Vikings to eight wins in twelve starts and returned to the postseason as a starter for the first time since 1988. However, the Vikings lost to the [[New York Giants]].\n\nAfter the season, McMahon joined the [[Arizona Cardinals]], now coached by Ryan, for the 1994 season, where he made his final career start in Week 3 against the [[Cleveland Browns]]. He finished the season as the team's third quarterback behind [[Steve Beuerlein]] and [[Jay Schroeder]] and left the team at its conclusion. After failing to catch on with the Browns in the 1995 preseason, McMahon joined the [[Green Bay Packers]]. He retired following the [[1996 NFL season|1996]] season, which finished with a Green Bay Super Bowl victory over the New England Patriots in New Orleans, eleven years to the day of the Bears' Super Bowl victory over the Patriots in the same venue.\n\nMcMahon caused some controversy when he showed up to the Packers' reception at the [[White House]] wearing his Bears jersey, due to the rivalry between the two teams. McMahon later explained that he did so because he was unable to visit the White House when he led the Bears to victory in Super Bowl XX; two days after the Bears won the game, the crew of [[Space Shuttle]] mission [[STS-51-L]] were killed in the [[Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|explosion]] of their craft, Shuttle ''[[Space Shuttle Challenger|Challenger]]'', and the Bears' scheduled visit was cancelled. McMahon and his surviving teammates and coaches were eventually received in 2011 by President [[Barack Obama]], himself a Bears fan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobears.com/news/ChalkTalkStory.asp?STORY_ID=4853|title=The Official Website of the Chicago Bears|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Post-retirement==\n\n===Legal trouble===\nSince retiring from football in [[1997 NFL season|1997]], he has worked as a restaurant owner and motivational speaker. He was apprehended in Florida for [[drunk driving]] in 2003. Upon being pulled over, McMahon allegedly got out of his car and said to the police, \"I'm too drunk; you got me.\"<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=1658175 \"McMahon 'wasted' while driving\"], ESPN.com, Accessed December 10, 2006</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 2012 it was reported by the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', that McMahon was targeted by the [[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation]] (FDIC) for $104 million in bad loans made by the now closed, Chicago-based [[Broadway Bank (Illinois)|Broadway Bank]], of which he was a member of the board. The FDIC wanted to recover $104 million in loans made by the bank before it was shut down, according to the newspaper. In addition to McMahon, six other former Broadway Bank board members and two former bank executives had been targeted. It is said that McMahon had only approved one loan out of the 17 bad loans for a $28 million Miami beach condo project. The FDIC said the bank lost $19.5 million on the loan, according to the ''Sun-Times''. McMahon said in a statement to the ''Sun-Times'' that the FDIC's claims were without merit and he expected to be vindicated. \"I am proud to have served as an outside, independent director for a brief part of the bank's history,\" he wrote, according to the ''Sun-Times''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/blogs/chicago/feds-target-former-bears-qb-mcmahon-145949993.html/|title=Feds target former Bears QB McMahon|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Concussions===\nIn a November 6, 2010, interview, McMahon admitted to having memory problems due to injuries suffered on the football field. McMahon was quoted as saying, 'There are a lot of times when I walk into a room and forget why I walked in there.'<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/ct-spt-1107-around-town--20101105,0,7989581,print.column|work=Chicago Tribune|title=Chicagotribune.Com|first1=Fred|last1=Mitchell|first2=David|last2=Kaplan|date=November 6, 2010}}</ref> McMahon, along with six other retired professional football players, filed a class action lawsuit against the NFL in August 2011, citing the league's negligence and misconduct in its handling of concussion-related injuries; the suit followed lawsuits filed shortly before by 75 other NFL retirees making similar claims as well as asserting that the NFL knew about the dangers concussions posed to NFL athletes as far back as the 1920s and actively withheld the information from the affected and the general public until the summer of 2010. The August suit that McMahon joined seeks to expand the scope of the suit to potentially all NFL players who suffered game-related concussions or head injuries.<ref>{{cite web|last=Associated Press|title=Players accuse NFL of negligence|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/6874906/jim-mcmahon-other-players-sue-nfl-concussions|publisher=espn.com|accessdate=March 19, 2012|date=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared in a ''Sports Illustrated'' cover article in September 2012 detailing his struggles.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csnchicago.com/football-chicago-bears/bears-talk/Sports-Illustrated-features-McMahon-real?blockID=768219&feedID=10330 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130121184635/http://www.csnchicago.com/football-chicago-bears/bears-talk/Sports-Illustrated-features-McMahon-real?blockID=768219&feedID=10330 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 21, 2013 |title=Sports Illustrated features McMahon, reality of concussions |last=Falcone |first=Nina |date=September 5, 2012 |work=CSNChicago.com |accessdate=September 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 2012, it was reported that at age 53 McMahon had been diagnosed as being in the early stages of [[dementia]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hendrix|first=Maggie|title=Super Bowl-winning quarterback Jim McMahon says he wishes he had played baseball|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/super-bowl-winning-quarterback-jim-mcmahon-says-wishes-192055029--nfl.html|publisher=Yahoo!}}</ref>\n\nThe Sports Illustrated article caught the attention of New York Chiropractor Scott Rosa who reached out to McMahon with an offer of treatment. Rosa believed that McMahon's neck was out of alignment caused by his years of playing football. Rosa performed an adjustment on his neck that repaired a blockage and allowed spinal fluid to drain normally. The procedure had positive results. \u201cThe first time he did it, my head was so full of stuff it literally felt like the toilet flushing,\u201d he said. \u201cI could actually feel the stuff draining out of my head.\u201d McMahon had daily adjustments for a week and now only returns for an adjustment every 3 months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pilotonline.com/sports/columnist/harry-minium/article_0cb3ba9f-4b24-551d-98c5-30a86b8a83d8.html|title=Ex-NFL star Jim McMahon was nearly driven to suicide by headaches from too many head blows|last=Minium|first=Harry|website=Virginian-Pilot|language=en|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> This treatment has led to improvement in his short term memory and the elimination of his headaches.<ref name=\"sfchronicle.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/sports/ostler/article/Ex-NFL-star-Jim-McMahon-spreading-gospel-of-golf-11290279.php|title=Ex-NFL star Jim McMahon spreading gospel of golf, new treatment - SFChronicle.com|date=2017-07-15|website=www.sfchronicle.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref>\n\n===Medical cannabis===\nMcMahon uses [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] to treat the chronic pain and arthritis that he suffers from as a result of his football career.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Magers|first1=Ron|title=Jim Mcmahon Says Medical Marijuana Helped Him Kick Pain Pill Habit|url=http://abc7chicago.com/news/jim-mcmahon-says-marijuana-helped-him-kick-pain-pills/1177764/|accessdate=June 9, 2016|work=ABC7 Eyewitness News|date=January 28, 2016}}</ref>  He calls cannabis a \"godsend\" that allowed him to completely eliminate his painkiller habit which he says included 100 [[Percocet]] pills a month.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCoppin|first1=Robert|title=Ex-Bear Jim McMahon: Medical marijuana got me off narcotic pain pills|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-chicago-bears-jim-mcmahon-medical-marijuana-met-20160128-story.html|accessdate=June 9, 2016|work=Chicago Tribune|date=January 29, 2016}}</ref>  McMahon has been active in speaking about his experience using cannabis, serving as spokesperson for the Cannabis Sports Policy Project<ref>{{cite press release |title=North American Cannabis Holdings and Former Chicago Bears QB Jim McMahon Announce The Cannabis Sports Policy Project |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/north-american-cannabis-holdings-and-former-chicago-bears-qb-jim-mcmahon-announce-the-cannabis-sports-policy-project-576210791.html |agency=PR Newswire |date=April 19, 2016 |access-date=June 9, 2016}}</ref> and a member of the Gridiron Cannabis Coalition along with several other former NFL players.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blackburn|first1=Peter|title=Ex-NFL stars use Netflix to share pro-cannabis PSA calling out Roger Goodell|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/watch-ex-nfl-stars-use-netflix-to-share-pro-cannabis-psa-calling-out-roger-goodell/|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=CBS Sports|date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>  McMahon appeared in a TV ad supporting cannabis legalization in the state of Arizona.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peake|first1=Gage|title=Ex-Bears QB Jim McMahon Stumps for Arizona Legalization|url=https://www.leafly.com/news/politics/ex-bears-qb-jim-mcmahon-stumps-arizona-legalization|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=Leafly|date=October 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, McMahon was among the signatories of an [[open letter]] addressed to the NFL, urging a change in the league's policy towards cannabis.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jhabvala|first1=Nicki|title=Players, Doctors for Cannabis Regulation pen letter to NFL urging policy reform|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2016/11/11/players-doctors-for-cannabis-regulation-pen-letter-nfl/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|work=The Denver Post|date=November 11, 2016}}</ref>  The letter was penned by [[Doctors for Cannabis Regulation]] and signed by several other NFL players.<ref>{{cite |title=An Open Letter to the National Football League |url=https://dfcr.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/NFL-open-letter.pdf |publisher=Doctors for Cannabis Regulation |date=November 11, 2016}}</ref>  McMahon is also a member of the Doctors for Cannabis Regulation NFL steering committee.<ref>{{cite web |title=NFL Campaign |url=https://dfcr.org/nfl-campaign/ |website=Doctors for Cannabis Regulation |accessdate=October 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other activities===\n[[Image:Jim McMahon in Iraq with the 15th MEU.jpg|thumb|right|225px|McMahon being greeted by the Commanding Officer of the [[15th MEU]] during his [[USO]] tour in [[Iraq]] in December 2006.]]\nIn December 2006 McMahon went to [[Iraq]] with the [[United Service Organizations|USO]] to visit American forces in the field.<ref>\n{{cite web|authorlink=United States Marine Corps|title=Celebrities drop in to pay the 15th MEU a holiday visit|publisher=15th Marine Expeditionary Unit|url=http://www.usmc.mil/15thmeu/PAGES/PHOTO_PAGES/070111_celeb_visit.htm}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Super Bowl XLIV]], McMahon joined other members of the 1985 Chicago Bears in resurrecting the [[Super Bowl Shuffle]] in a [[Boost Mobile]] commercial.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jon Greenberg |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/nfl/columns/story?columnist=greenberg_jon&id=4827883 |title=Chicago Bears' \"Super Bowl Shuffle\" an enduring, endearing sports moment \u2013 ESPN Chicago |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=January 15, 2010 |accessdate=July 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, McMahon became a part owner of the [[Indoor Football League]]'s [[Chicago Slaughter]].\n\nIn November 2012, McMahon appeared on an episode of the sitcom ''[[The League]]'' called \"The Tailgate.\"\n\n==Playing style==\nThroughout his career, McMahon was known for both on- and off-field antics. Most famously, his wearing of a [[headband]] while on the sidelines once led to him being fined by then NFL commissioner, [[Pete Rozelle]], as it had an unauthorized corporate logo (Adidas) on it. The next week his headband simply said \"Rozelle\". (The commissioner later admitted in a letter to McMahon that the headband with Rozelle's name was \"funny as hell\", but declined to rescind the $5,000 fine.) Reportedly before Super Bowl XX hundreds of fans mailed McMahon headbands in hopes he would wear them during the game; Rozelle warned the quarterback not to wear anything \"unacceptable\". In response, McMahon decided to help bring attention to [[Diabetes mellitus type 1|Juvenile Diabetes]] by wearing a headband simply stating \"JDF Cure\", before switching to one stating \"[[National League of Families POW/MIA Flag|POW-MIA]]\", and finally one with the word \"Pluto\", the nickname of his close friend and favorite collegiate receiving target, former BYU wide receiver Danny Plater, who was afflicted with a brain tumor.<ref>Benson, Lee. And They Came to Pass. Salt Lake City: Deseret Book, 1988. Print.\n</ref>\n\nHe also is known for his trademark sunglasses, which he wears for medical reasons. At age six, while trying to untie a knot in a toy gun holster with a fork, he accidentally severed the cornea in his right eye when the fork slipped. While his [[visual perception|vision]] was saved, the accident left that eye extremely sensitive to [[light]].<ref>''[[America's Game: The Super Bowl Champions]]'', \"#2. 1985 Chicago Bears.\" Premiered on [[CBS]], February 3, 2007</ref> On the field he was among the first to wear a helmet fitted with a tinted plastic visor covering the eyes, leading to nicknames like \"Darth Vader\" and \"Black Sunshine.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiedeman |first1=Reeves |title=What's in a Nickname? |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/sporting-scene/whats-in-a-nickname |website=The New Yorker |accessdate=August 21, 2018 |date=October 7, 2011}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nMcMahon occasionally would play wearing gloves, and urged former NFL quarterback [[David Carr (American football)|David Carr]] to also wear gloves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carolinagrowl.com/Read.aspx?Story=235|title=HugeDomains.com - CarolinaGrowl.com is for sale (Carolina Growl)|website=www.carolinagrowl.com}}</ref>\n\n==Career stats==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! G\n! Passing<br />Att.-Comp.\n! Yards\n! Pct.\n! TD\n! Int.\n! Sacks-Lost\n! Pass<br />Rating\n|-\n| [[1982 Chicago Bears season|1982]]\n| rowspan=\"7\"|[[Chicago Bears|Chicago]]\n| 8\n| 210\u2013120\n| 1,501\n| .571\n| 9\n| 7\n| 27\u2013196\n| 79.9\n|-\n| [[1983 Chicago Bears season|1983]]\n| 14\n| 295\u2013175\n| 2,184\n| .593\n| 12\n| 13\n| 42\u2013266\n| 77.6\n|-\n| [[1984 Chicago Bears season|1984]]\n| 9\n| 143\u201385\n| 1,146\n| .594\n| 8\n| 2\n| 10\u201348\n| 97.8\n|-\n| [[1985 Chicago Bears season|1985]]\n| 13\n| 313\u2013178\n| 2,392\n| .569\n| 15\n| 11\n| 26\u2013125\n| 82.6\n|-\n| [[1986 Chicago Bears season|1986]]\n| 6\n| 150\u201377\n| 995\n| .513\n| 5\n| 8\n| 6\u201340\n| 61.4\n|-\n| [[1987 Chicago Bears season|1987]]\n| 7\n| 210\u2013125\n| 1,639\n| .595\n| 12\n| 8\n| 22\u2013136\n| 87.4\n|-\n| [[1988 Chicago Bears season|1988]]\n| 9\n| 192\u2013114\n| 1,346\n| .594\n| 6\n| 7\n| 13\u201379\n| 76.0\n|-\n| [[1989 San Diego Chargers season|1989]]\n| [[San Diego Chargers|San Diego]]\n| 12\n| 318\u2013176\n| 2,132\n| .553\n| 10\n| 10\n| 28\u2013167\n| 73.5\n|-\n| [[1990 Philadelphia Eagles season|1990]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[Philadelphia Eagles|Philadelphia]]\n| 5\n| 9\u20136\n| 63\n| .667\n| 0\n| 0\n| 1\u20137\n| 86.8\n|-\n| [[1991 Philadelphia Eagles season|1991]]\n| 12\n| 311\u2013187\n| 2,239\n| .601\n| 12\n| 11\n| 21\u2013128\n| 80.3\n|-\n| [[1992 Philadelphia Eagles season|1992]]\n| 4\n| 43\u201322\n| 279\n| .512\n| 1\n| 2\n| 4\u201325\n| 60.1\n|-\n| [[1993 Minnesota Vikings season|1993]]\n| [[Minnesota Vikings|Minnesota]]\n| 12\n| 331\u2013200\n| 1,968\n| .604\n| 9\n| 8\n| 23\u2013104\n| 76.2\n|-\n| [[1994 Arizona Cardinals season|1994]]\n| [[Arizona Cardinals|Arizona]]\n| 3\n| 43\u201323\n| 219\n| .535\n| 1\n| 3\n| 3\u201323\n| 46.6\n|-\n| [[1995 Green Bay Packers season|1995]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Green Bay Packers|Green Bay]]\n| 1\n| 1\u20131\n| 6\n| 1.00\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\u20130\n| 91.7\n|-\n| [[1996 Green Bay Packers season|1996]]\n| 5\n| 4\u20133\n| 39\n| .750\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\u20130\n| 105.2\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Totals\n| 120\n| 2,573\u20131,492\n| 18,148\n| .580\n| 100\n| 90\n| 226\u20131,344\n| 78.2\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Playoff Totals\n| 8\n| 155\u201382\n| 1,112\n| .643\n| 5\n| 4\n| n/a-n/a\n| 76.1\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nMcMahon met Nancy Daines at BYU, and the couple married in 1982 after four years of dating.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Benson|first1=Lee|title=And They Came To Pass|date=1988}}</ref> They have four children together and divorced in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rodkin|first1=Denis|title=Jim McMahon Sells His Northbrook Home|url=http://www.chicagomag.com/Radar/Deal-Estate/October-2009/Jim-McMahon-Sells-His-Northbrook-Home/|publisher=Chicago Magazine}}</ref> He was in a romantic relationship with Laurie Navon who was cited in the Sports Illustrated article where his health was discussed.<ref name=\":0\" /> The specifics of his relationship with Navon are not known, but more recent media reports currently have him in a relationship with Mayra Montoya.<ref name=\"sfchronicle.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zimbio.com/photos/Jim+McMahon/2018+Derek+Jeter+Celebrity+Invitational+Gala/t12ni6um0nd|title=Jim McMahon Photos Photos: 2018 Derek Jeter Celebrity Invitational Gala|website=Zimbio|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of NCAA Division I FBS quarterbacks with at least 80 career passing touchdowns]]\n* [[List of NCAA major college football yearly passing leaders]]\n* [[List of NCAA major college football yearly total offense leaders]]\n*[[List of NFL players with chronic traumatic encephalopathy#Living former players diagnosed with or reporting symptoms of CTE|Living former players diagnosed with or reporting symptoms of chronic traumatic encephalopathy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jim McMahon}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.swangwear.com}}\n* {{cfbhof|id=2043|name=Jim McMahon}}\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=MCM166115 |espn=6406 |cbs= |yahoo= |si= |pfr=M/McMaJi00 |rotoworld=}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Jim McMahon\u2014navboxes\n| list1 = \n{{Super Bowl XX}}\n{{Super Bowl XXXI}}\n{{Davey O'Brien Award}}\n{{1981 NCAA Division I-A College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{1982 NFL Draft}}\n{{BearsFirstPick}}\n{{Bears1982DraftPicks}}\n{{Super Bowl Champion quarterbacks}}\n{{NFL Comeback Players of the Year}}\n{{NCAA major college football passing yardage leaders}}\n{{BYU Cougars quarterback navbox}}\n{{Chicago Bears starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{San Diego Chargers starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Philadelphia Eagles starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Minnesota Vikings starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Arizona Cardinals starting quarterback navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McMahon, Jim}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:BYU Cougars football players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:Legends Foo