{"title_page": "Charlie Is My Darling (film)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 Ireland 1965 \n| image          = Charlie is My Darling 2012 DVD cover.jpg\n| caption        = Poster for the 2012 restored version\n| director       =[[Peter Whitehead (filmmaker)|Peter Whitehead]] (1966) and [[Michael Gochanour]] (2012)\n| producer       = [[Andrew Loog Oldham]] (1966)<br>Robin Klein (2012)\n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[The Rolling Stones]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Peter Whitehead (filmmaker)|Peter Whitehead]]\n| editing        = [[Peter Whitehead (filmmaker)|Peter Whitehead]] (1966)<br>Nathan Punwar (2012)\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|1966|10||[[International Filmfestival Mannheim-Heidelberg|IFFMH]]|2012|09|29|[[New York Film Festival|NYFF]]|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 64 minutes\n| country        = UK (1966 version)<br>USA (2012 version)\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n'''''Charlie Is My Darling''''', directed by [[Peter Whitehead (filmmaker)|Peter Whitehead]] and produced by [[the Rolling Stones]]' manager [[Andrew Loog Oldham]], was the first documentary film about the Rolling Stones. It was intended as a screen test for the band, to see how their musical charisma would translate into film. The footage was shot during [[The Rolling Stones 2nd Irish Tour 1965|the band's second tour of Ireland]] that year, on 3 and 4 September 1965, and was finished in the spring of 1966.<ref name=\"nzentgraf\">{{cite web |last =Zentgraf |first=Nico |title=The Complete Works of the Rolling Stones 1962\u20132008 |url=http://www.nzentgraf.de/books/tcw/works1.htm|accessdate=16 November 2009}}</ref> It was given its premiere at the [[International Filmfestival Mannheim-Heidelberg|Mannheim Film Festival]] in October 1966.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iffmh.de/en/1966/Films |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130206213343/http://www.iffmh.de/en/1966/Films |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 February 2013 |title=Films in 1966 |work=[[International Filmfestival Mannheim-Heidelberg]] |accessdate=7 February 2013 }}</ref> But the film was never officially released, due to the legal fights between the Rolling Stones and [[Allen Klein]]<ref>[http://s120937152.websitehome.co.uk/pw/html/charlie.html Peter Whitehead's website: ''Charlie is My Darling''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917172144/http://s120937152.websitehome.co.uk/pw/html/charlie.html |date=17 September 2008 }}. Retrieved 2 December 2012</ref> and a burglary in Andrew Loog Oldham's office, which saw all prints disappear.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130201031550/http://rebeccakemp.com/pages/features/charlie-is-my-darling.php Rebecca Kemp interview with Andrew Loog Oldham]. Retrieved 2 December 2012</ref>\n\nNearly fifty years later, in 2012, a new film using restored footage and entitled ''Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 Ireland 1965'' was released by Allen Klein's [[ABKCO Records]], which owns the rights to all older Stones material. ''Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 Ireland 1965'' came about when director [[Michael Gochanour]] discovered additional unprocessed footage of the 1965 Rolling Stones screen test. Gochanour spent two years editing and remixing the '60s material, adding a story line and synching music to Rolling Stones concert footage that had originally been filmed without sound. The result was ''Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 1965''. One of Gochanour's objectives in making the film was \"to show The Rolling Stones in a way the world had never seen them before; as a band just coming into their own \u2013 raw, visceral, innocent and with purpose.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mickgochanour.com/directors-statement-2.html | title=Director's statement - The Rolling Stones - Ireland 1965 (a/k/a Charlie is my Darling) | date=2013 | publisher=Mick Gochanour | accessdate=9 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe 64-minute documentary, ''Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 Ireland 1965'', follows the group from their car trip out of London to [[London Heathrow Airport|Heathrow Airport]], and from there to [[Dublin]] where they had two concerts at the Adelphi Theatre on 3 September. The next day they take a train up to [[Belfast]] for two concerts at the ABC Theatre, before returning to London by plane the following day.Besides stage shots from the concerts (where the second Dublin concert ends in total chaos as fans storm the stage), the film contains scenes from a hotel room in Dublin (where Keith and Mick for fun do a few [[Beatles]] songs as well as a couple of their own), scenes from their train trip to Belfast, another impromptu song session by a piano (with both Keith and Andrew Oldham playing the piano while Mick impersonates [[Elvis Presley]] and sings [[Fats Domino]]'s version of \"[[Blueberry Hill (song)|Blueberry Hill]]\"), and finally their flight back to London. Intermixed with this are interviews with the band members where they talk about fame, fans and future.\n \n''Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 Ireland 1965'' premiered at the Walter Reade Theater in New York City on 29 September 2012, as part of the 2012 [[New York Film Festival]], and was released on DVD and Blu-ray in November 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/rolling-stones-set-premiere-date-for-tour-documentary-20120827 |date=27 August 2012 |accessdate=8 November 2012 |title=Rolling Stones Set Premiere Date for Tour Documentary |work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> On 25 November 2012, it was shown by [[BBC Two]] as part of BBC's \"The Rolling Stones at 50\" celebrations.\n\n==Charts==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2012)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Argentinian Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adminlic.capif.org.ar/sis_resultados_rankings_web.aspx |title=Rankings |work=[[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers|CAPIF]] |language=Spanish |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110035036/http://adminlic.capif.org.ar/sis_resultados_rankings_web.aspx |archivedate=10 November 2011 }} ''Select'' Ranking Mensual de DVD ''under the first drop-down menu and select'' 1 November 2012 ''under the second menu.''</ref>\n|3\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australian Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite journal |date=19 November 2012 |title=ARIA Top 40 Music DVD |journal=[[ARIA Charts|The ARIA Report]] |issue=1186 |page=23 |format=PDF |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/23790/20121204-1257/Issue1186.pdf}}</ref>\n|13\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Austrian Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://austriancharts.at/weekchart.asp?cat=d&year=2012&date=20121116 |title=Austria Top 40 \u2013 Musik-DVDs Top 10 16.11.2012 |publisher=Austriancharts.com |language=German |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102180938/http://austriancharts.at/weekchart.asp?cat=d&year=2012&date=20121116 |archivedate=2 November 2013 }}</ref>\n|3\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Danish Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitlisterne.dk/lister.asp?w=46&y=2012&list=v10 |title=Musik DVD Top-10 |work=Hitlisten.nu |publisher=[[IFPI Denmark]] |language=Danish |accessdate=7 February 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130412102403/http://www.hitlisterne.dk/lister.asp?w=46&y=2012&list=v10 |archive-date=12 April 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Dutch Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dutchcharts.nl/weekchart.asp?cat=d&year=2012&date=20121110 |title=Dutch Charts Portal |work=[[GfK]] Dutch Charts |publisher=Hung Medien |language=Dutch |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324115809/http://www.dutchcharts.nl/weekchart.asp?cat=d&year=2012&date=20121110 |archivedate=24 March 2015 }}</ref>\n|12\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|German Albums Chart<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.de/album.asp?artist=The+Rolling+Stones&title=Charlie+Is+My+Darling+-+Ireland+1965+&#91;DVD&#93;&country=de |title=Album \u2013 The Rolling Stones, Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 Ireland 1965 &#91;DVD&#93; |work=Charts.de |publisher=[[Media Control Charts|Media Control]] |language=German |accessdate=7 February 2013}}</ref>\n|54\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Irish Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irma.ie/aucharts.asp |title=Irish Charts \u2013 Singles, Albums & Compilations |work=[[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105120403/http://www.irma.ie/aucharts.asp |archivedate=5 November 2012 |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|3\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Italian Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fimi.it/classifiche_result_dvd.php?anno=2012&mese=11&id=416 |title=Classifiche |work=[[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]] |language=Italian |accessdate=7 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305041256/http://www.fimi.it/classifiche_result_dvd.php?anno=2012&mese=11&id=416 |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|12\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Spanish Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.promusicae.es/files/listassemanales/dvds/historial/TOP%2020%20DVD%2012_45.pdf |title=Top 20 DVD Musical |work=[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]] |publisher=Media Control GfK International |language=Spanish |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023060402/http://www.promusicae.es/files/listassemanales/dvds/historial/TOP%2020%20DVD%2012_45.pdf |archivedate=23 October 2013 }}</ref>\n|14\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Swedish Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sverigetopplistan.se/ |title=Sveriges Officiella Topplista |work=[[Sverigetopplistan]] |language=Swedish |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226145037/http://www.sverigetopplistan.se/ |archivedate=26 December 2015 }} ''Search for'' Charlie Is My Darling ''and click'' S\u00f6k.</ref>\n|6\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Swiss Music DVDs Charts<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swisscharts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=d&year=2012&date=20121118 |title=Swiss Charts \u2013 Music DVD Top 10 18.11.2012 |work=Hitparade.ch |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412234417/http://swisscharts.com/weekchart.asp?year=2012&date=20121118&cat=d |archivedate=12 April 2013 }}</ref>\n|8\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|UK Music Videos Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/video-archive-chart/_/29/2012-11-17/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130411141555/http://www.officialcharts.com/video-archive-chart/_/29/2012-11-17/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 April 2013 |title=2012-11-17 Top 40 Music Video Archive |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=7 February 2013 }}</ref>\n|11\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0060231|title=Charlie Is My Darling}}\n*[http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/framework_the_journal_of_cinema_and_media/summary/v052/52.1.article04.html ''Variety'', 26 October 1966: ''Charlie is My Darling'', review]. Retrieved 2 December 2012\n*[http://www.theartsdesk.com/new-music/story-charlie-my-darling The Arts Desk, 26 November 2012: ''The Story of Charlie Is My Darling'']. Retrieved 2 December 2012\n* [http://www.abkco.com/index.php/films/film/12 Official website for the new, restored version]. Retrieved 2 December 2012\n*[http://ultimateclassicrock.com/the-rolling-stones-charlie-is-my-darling-ireland-1965-dvd-review/ Ultimate Classic Rock, November 2012: \"The Rolling Stones, ''Charlie is My Darling'' \u2013 Ireland 1965\" \u2013 DVD review]. Retrieved 2 December 2012\n* [http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/movies/2012/10/charlie-is-my-darling-the-rolling-stones-in-65.html Richard Brody, ''The New Yorker'', 3 October 2012: ''\"Charlie is My Darling\": The Rolling Stones in 1965'']. Retrieved 2 December 2012\n\n{{The Rolling Stones}}\n{{The_Rolling_Stones_videos}}\n\n[[Category:1966 films]]\n[[Category:1960s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white documentary films]]\n[[Category:British documentary films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ireland]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:Rockumentaries]]\n[[Category:The Rolling Stones films]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 Ireland 1965 \n| image          = Charlie is My Darling 2012 DVD cover.jpg\n| caption        = Poster for the 2012 restored version\n| director       =[[Peter Whitehead (filmmaker)|Peter Whitehead]] (1966) and [[Michael Gochanour]] (2012)\n| producer       = [[Andrew Loog Oldham]] (1966)<br>Robin Klein (2012)\n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[The Rolling Stones]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Peter Whitehead (filmmaker)|Peter Whitehead]]\n| editing        = [[Peter Whitehead (filmmaker)|Peter Whitehead]] (1966)<br>Nathan Punwar (2012)\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|1966|10||[[International Filmfestival Mannheim-Heidelberg|IFFMH]]|2012|09|29|[[New York Film Festival|NYFF]]|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 64 minutes\n| country        = UK (1966 version)<br>USA (2012 version)\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n'''''Charlie Is My Darling''''', directed by [[Peter Whitehead (filmmaker)|Peter Whitehead]] and produced by [[the Rolling Stones]]' manager [[Andrew Loog Oldham]], was the first documentary film about the Rolling Stones. It was intended as a screen test for the band, to see how their musical charisma would translate into film. The footage was shot during [[The Rolling Stones 2nd Irish Tour 1965|the band's second tour of Ireland]] that year, on 3 and 4 September 1965, and was finished in the spring of 1966.<ref name=\"nzentgraf\">{{cite web |last =Zentgraf |first=Nico |title=The Complete Works of the Rolling Stones 1962\u20132008 |url=http://www.nzentgraf.de/books/tcw/works1.htm|accessdate=16 November 2009}}</ref> It was given its premiere at the [[International Filmfestival Mannheim-Heidelberg|Mannheim Film Festival]] in October 1966.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iffmh.de/en/1966/Films |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130206213343/http://www.iffmh.de/en/1966/Films |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 February 2013 |title=Films in 1966 |work=[[International Filmfestival Mannheim-Heidelberg]] |accessdate=7 February 2013 }}</ref> But the film was never officially released, due to the legal fights between the Rolling Stones and [[Allen Klein]]<ref>[http://s120937152.websitehome.co.uk/pw/html/charlie.html Peter Whitehead's website: ''Charlie is My Darling''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917172144/http://s120937152.websitehome.co.uk/pw/html/charlie.html |date=17 September 2008 }}. Retrieved 2 December 2012</ref> and a burglary in Andrew Loog Oldham's office, which saw all prints disappear.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130201031550/http://rebeccakemp.com/pages/features/charlie-is-my-darling.php Rebecca Kemp interview with Andrew Loog Oldham]. Retrieved 2 December 2012</ref>\n\nNearly fifty years later, in 2012, a new film using restored footage and entitled ''Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 Ireland 1965'' was released by Allen Klein's [[ABKCO Records]], which owns the rights to all older Stones material. ''Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 Ireland 1965'' came about when director [[Michael Gochanour|Michael (Mick) Gochanour]] discovered additional unprocessed footage of the 1965 Rolling Stones screen test. Gochanour spent two years editing and remixing the 60's material, adding a story line and synching music to Rolling Stones concert footage that had originally been filmed without sound. The result was ''Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 1965'' directed by Peter Whitehead and Michael Gochanour. One of Gochanour's objectives in making the film was \"to show The Rolling Stones in a way the world had never seen them before; as a band just coming into their own \u2013 raw, visceral, innocent and with purpose.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mickgochanour.com/directors-statement-2.html | title=Director's statement - The Rolling Stones - Ireland 1965 (a/k/a Charlie is my Darling) | date=2013 | publisher=Mick Gochanour | accessdate=9 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe 64-minute documentary, ''Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 Ireland 1965'', follows the group from their car trip out of London to [[London Heathrow Airport|Heathrow Airport]], and from there to [[Dublin]] where they had two concerts at the Adelphi Theatre on 3 September. The next day they take a train up to [[Belfast]] for two concerts at the ABC Theatre, before returning to London by plane the following day.Besides stage shots from the concerts (where the second Dublin concert ends in total chaos as fans storm the stage), the film contains scenes from a hotel room in Dublin (where Keith and Mick for fun do a few Beatles songs as well as a couple of their own), scenes from their train trip to Belfast, another impromptu song session by a piano (with both Keith and Andrew Oldham playing the piano while Mick impersonates Elvis Presley and sings Fats Domino's version of \"[[Blueberry Hill (song)|Blueberry Hill]]\"), and finally their flight back to London. Intermixed with this are interviews with the band members where they talk about fame, fans and future.\n \n''Charlie Is My Darling \u2013 Ireland 1965'' premiered at the Walter Reade Theater in New York City on 29 September 2012, as part of the 2012 [[New York Film Festival]], and was released on DVD and Blu-ray in November 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/rolling-stones-set-premiere-date-for-tour-documentary-20120827 |date=27 August 2012 |accessdate=8 November 2012 |title=Rolling Stones Set Premiere Date for Tour Documentary |work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> On 25 November 2012, it was shown by [[BBC Two]] as part of BBC's \"The Rolling Stones at 50\" celebrations.\n\n==Charts==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2012)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Argentinian Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adminlic.capif.org.ar/sis_resultados_rankings_web.aspx |title=Rankings |work=[[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers|CAPIF]] |language=Spanish |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110035036/http://adminlic.capif.org.ar/sis_resultados_rankings_web.aspx |archivedate=10 November 2011 }} ''Select'' Ranking Mensual de DVD ''under the first drop-down menu and select'' 1 November 2012 ''under the second menu.''</ref>\n|3\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australian Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite journal |date=19 November 2012 |title=ARIA Top 40 Music DVD |journal=[[ARIA Charts|The ARIA Report]] |issue=1186 |page=23 |format=PDF |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/23790/20121204-1257/Issue1186.pdf}}</ref>\n|13\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Austrian Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://austriancharts.at/weekchart.asp?cat=d&year=2012&date=20121116 |title=Austria Top 40 \u2013 Musik-DVDs Top 10 16.11.2012 |publisher=Austriancharts.com |language=German |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102180938/http://austriancharts.at/weekchart.asp?cat=d&year=2012&date=20121116 |archivedate=2 November 2013 }}</ref>\n|3\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Danish Music DVDs Chart<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitlisterne.dk/lister.asp?w=46&y=2012&list=v10 |title=